\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You've also got a Jewish name?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes. All Jewish Orthodox - and all kinds of
 children have a Hebrew name which is used - when they're being }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11168726\charrsid1644444 circumcised}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 , it's also used when they're being - when they're }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7426541 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  or when they're being confirmed. And it's - you have a name which is equivalent of your English name and you also - this name is }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11168726\charrsid1644444 coupled}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 with your father. And my - my name is the equivalent of the English Aaron - it's Haron. Haron. You've heard of Haron El Rashid haven't you? Well it's Haron Ben which is the son of - Mousha - my father's Hebrew name was Moses - Morris his nam
e was in Hebrew would be Mousha so I am Haron Ben Mousha. And in Hebrew - if I was in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Palestine{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - I would probably be known as Haron Ben Mousha.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Can you tell me your birthplace?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you have a big family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes. No sisters, all boys. Seven boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 They'd be very pleased wouldn't they in a Jewish family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Mother always wanted a girl though - she wanted a girl but never had any.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You don't remember how old your father was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh I can soon tell you. Y
es, I was born in 1900 and he was thirty-nine - he was - no, he died when he was thirty-nine. So if you go back from that - what year would that bring you to? Twenty-eight wouldn't it. Twenty-eight - what would be 19 - 18 -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Can you tell me where your father came from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes. He came from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Lithuania{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Yes. And my mother came from Lithuania.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 And they came over here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
They came over here - my mother's parents came over - they weren't really refugees, what happened was that my - mother's brothe
rs would have gone in - had to go into the Russian Army and to escape military service because the Jews were treated rather badly, they - there was an agency in Manchester that arranged for them to escape and - those that were younger than military age we
re all right and girls were all right but boys of military age had to hide. And I once knew a man who for many years had a wooden stump and he lost his leg being shot by the border guards in escaping from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Russia{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. So the majority managed to get through, they came through to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Riga{\*\xmlclose}
 on the Baltic coast and then got a boat and they either went to - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Hull{\*\xmlclose} or {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Liverpool{\*\xmlclose} or wherever it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Why did your father and mother choose {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}England{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Because - there were only two places they could really go to. The one was 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}America{\*\xmlclose} and one was {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}England{\*\xmlclose} and a lot of them came to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}America{\*\xmlclose} via 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}England{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 because I got relations who did exactly that. Now - I can tell more about me mother - mother's family. You see, my wife and I are cousins - so we have the same maternal grand -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Your allowed to marry a cousin in your faith?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Yes. First cousins, yes, oh yes. You are in most faiths I think. First - first cousins, yes. My mother and my wife's father were brother and sister you see. So I can tell you more about my mother's fami
ly. They came - my grandfather - my mother's father, came first with one of the - my uncles and they established themselves first of all in Leeds and eventually came to Manchester and my father must - I don't much - how my father came over but me mother a
nd father must have met in the early 1890's - 'cos I think they were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7426541 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 in 1896 or 1895 you see and my brother was born - couple of years before me - about 1898 and I was born in 1900. And - from then on they had the various children. But - my mother was about sixteen I think when she came over to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}England{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. She never had any formal schooling but she was able to speak English and write a bit and read the newspaper which a lot of the Jewish people never learnt to do - the elder ones. Used to read the Yiddish paper.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You told me your father's occupation was a builder?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
He was - he wasn't a builder originally, he was a - a decorator - a painter and decorator. But he'd come from a family that had a - a business - they used to do - they were tin smith
s and they in addition to the usual stuff that tinsmiths do they used to make these windows, these leaded windows - used to have in big halls and churches you know like you have window set in a lead frame like these - like these things. After these kind -
 well they did that sort of work in - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Russia{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. But he was actually trained as a - a painter and decorator. He came over are as a painter and decorator and worked for a while and then - met up - well he would - probably would with a lot of - builders and he -
 he had a natural talent - talent for surveying and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11168726\charrsid1644444 valuing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 property and he went out of decorating and painting and became a sort of a - a freelance valuer and he travelled not only to - from Manchester he went to Nottingham, he was friendly with a man cal
led John Ball who was the Mayor of Nottingham at the time, he went to London, went to a number of other places and he was instrumental in valuing property or land for building purposes and the whole - practically the whole of the Sedgley Park Estate was d
e
veloped as a result of this and for that he was made a - a partner, a working partner in a combination of Smith Derbyshire and Cahm and the Derbyshire was a very well known man because the whole of Kingsway was developed by George F Derbyshire and the Cli
ff Grange just down the road was developed by him but the other man, Smith was a - a man from Leeds and he was a bookmaker. He went under the name of George Drake, Frederick Smith I think was his name but his - turf name was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did your mother have a job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No. She didn't have a job then until she was a widow but she was at home you see. Because - with my father - being able to do these - valuation jobs he got a lot of fees and started doing quite well. As a matter of fact, the Franco-British Exhibit
ion had a - a building section and in 1907 or '08, my father and mother went to London to this building exhibition the reason why I remember that is that one of the things they did, if you had a pocket watch, they used to take the top - the glass off and 
they'd paint the - tricolour and the union jack in miniature on the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11168726\charrsid1644444  front of the watch as a moment}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 , and he had a watch with these two flags painted on it - that's show I remember it you see. That was in 1907 - 1908. And he did so well that he decided he wou
ld like to send his sons to boarding school. Three of us went - three. We went to a school in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Margate{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. And - we did - we must have done quite well. It was then that we moved from - into {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Salford{\*\xmlclose} because - we wanted be near to Sedgley and the eventually we got there but - via 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Great Clowes Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Right opposite the Cliff. Number three hundred and eighty-four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Can you tell me what job your}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11168726\charrsid1644444  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 mother did do eventually when she was left a widow?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 She worked in a cap - cap making factory. Yes. She was make - making caps.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You don't know the hours she worked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No, I don't remember very much about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Was it a full time job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes, I think it was, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Who looked after you as children if }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11168726\charrsid1644444 your mother}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  was out at work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I don't think anybody looked after us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You looked after yourselves?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes. Well I - what I ought to tell you was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 It would be later - you'd be older then of course?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
I was getting on then - I'd be about fourteen or fifteen then. But two of my brothe
rs, you see, with having such a big family that the Jewish organizations said that we couldn't manage to keep this family altogether and two of my brothers were sent to a school in London, the Norwood School for Jewish Children - an orphanage, and two of 
my brothers went there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 This would be very upsetting to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh of course it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How many children were there altogether?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Seven of us. Seven boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Was there a big difference in ages?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I was second one. My eldest brot
her was about - nearly two years older than me, he died about ten years ago. He went to this boarding school with us, then went to the High Grade school and then left, 'cos you were allowed to leave at fourteen and - he went into a waterproof factory - wo
r
ked as a waterproofer and on few occasions I used to go and - help him because one of the jobs they had to do was when they used to - fix the garments together with rubber solution the surface solution had to be brushed off and one of the jobs which boys 
d
id was with a stiff brush rub all the bits off and it was a - was an awful job, it was a hard job but - what I remember most was that this was before the times when you had canteens or separate eating rooms I used to take me lunch with me and - after an h
our or so in the factory, in this waterproof factory where there was all this }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11168726\charrsid1644444 naphtha}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  by the time I came to eat me lunch it tasted like eating rubber solution, I didn't like it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How old would you be when you did that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I must have been about - oh 
- fifteen - fourteen or fifteen. To help out. Well it wasn't really - I used to help him you see. Then he left that and went on market selling sweets. And the firm that made the sweets was the famous firm of Liddlands in Salford - used to make boiled swee
ts on Broad Street there or somewhere round the back, they were very well-known, and he used to take these sweets and go on the different markets and I used to go with him to help.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 So you've had lots of part time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Little jobs. I must tell yo
u about this - you know what used to happen - it may be a bit of a joke. You had to pay - a market fee you see, a stall fee but - what they used to do was that one person used to buy a stall fee and get a little receipt for it, ticket, and then pass it ro
u
nd in front of the inspector coming along and I - as an innocent child - did - did that without knowing what was going on and - I remember getting - I don't know whether I was caught or not but - I - they must have believed me because I was quite innocent
 
of what was going on and they never said anything to me - of course I was a child so it didn't make much difference but that went on - they'd pay one ten shilling fee and it did for about five or six stalls. Then in a very strange way - there is something
 which is much more sordid than that - we had lodgers in some of the houses -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How many rooms were there at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Therlmere Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh it wasn't a bad house. It had - two reception rooms and a kitchen and about three bedrooms - and a bathroom but an out - outside toilet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did anyone else either than your family live in that house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Not there. We had a - we had a maid for a little while. A woman to come in to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11168726\charrsid1644444 help}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  - used to come in and live with us - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did she have any help in the house later on?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 She may have done - I can't remember that, no. I don't think so. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Was the washing done at home or sent out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No, never sent out. It was always done at home - 'cos I remember going down in the cellar with the dolly and doing - d
oing this with the - this wooden thing with the legs and doing this, and helping with the wringer - these very big old fashioned wringers you know - I used to wind the - the big wooden rollers. We used to do that in the cellar. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11168726\charrsid1644444 your mother}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  or father make or mend the family's clothes? Or shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No. Always - Coombs used to do ours - you could get 'em done for half a crown or three and six in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How often did you have new clothes and where were they bought?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh - we bough
t - Lewis - Lewis's bought a few - at Passover, it was very common, Passover and the Jewish New Year was a season for having new clothes. It's like Whit week - like Whit Week, yes. Passover and the New Year - mainly at Passover. And of course at New Year 
as well because the children used to like to go to the synagogue and look - well in all their family, see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 When did you have new shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well - you see, I don't remember any real hardship - in as much a I - I never had many clothes, you see, when 
I - I had to sit for the grammar school - examination and my suit wasn't good enough to go and - I had to borrow a cousin's suit to go to the examination. And - they gave me a suit - or they lent me a suit and later on whilst I was at the grammar school t
he headmaster called me once and said there was a fund which provided and I got a suit made - out of these funds because }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11168726\charrsid1644444 my clothes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  were - a bit }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11168726\charrsid1644444 dilapidated}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did your father help around the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I doubt that very much because he was away a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Not undress you or dress you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No, no, he was never done, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you have any regular jobs to do at home to help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Before I was eleven? No, I was treated like a gentleman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Was this a custom in Jewish homes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No, no. No, no, 
no. We happened to be - sufficiently good circumstances for me not to have to do anything you see. We had these maids occasionally you see. Living in - and - no, I never helped in the house. Used to go errands.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you help the younger children with t
heir dressing or did they help you in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Not until later. Not until I was about fifteen or sixteen. 'Cos my younger brothers, I remember once one of my younger brothers had a severe attack of rheumatic fever and it was my job to - he had an att
ack of this rheumatic fever and it way my job to lift him out of bed and do things for him - it was horrible. It was a very painful - there was nobody else to do anything - but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 That was the only job you ever did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well you see - we're not doing
 this in a very good order because that happened in from 1916 onwards when we lived at a shop. But you want the time prior to that really don't you? No, the only time was after the father died - until the time my father died I was treated like a little ge
n
tleman 'cos when we went to this boarding school during the summer months we were in white flannels all the time All day long in white flannels. And I can remember one - one year - we were only there two years - well one year me mother came and stayed six
 weeks at a hotel in - Margate, to be with us. So you can imagine that we weren't badly off if she could come and stay for six weeks while we were at the school. And I - I went to Lewis's yesterday and we - I bought a pair of -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 The hardship only really came when your father died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh yes, after my father died, yes. That was - that was bad after that. When I say bad, it - I never really experienced any severe hardship, no - I don't remember ever going hungry. I can never remember going hungry. I ma
y not have had the clothes and we may not have had the - things inside the house but I can never remember going hungry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
You don't ever remember seeing your mother go without so that you could have things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well she must - she must have done but -
 I don't think that that ever - I don't think we were ever in such circumstances that - the food had to be shared out - a small amount of food shared out between us, I don't think I can remember that - I don't think it ever occurred. Because - 'cos other 
m
embers of the family would do something you see. When - when my father died my - mother's brothers organized a dance in order to raise some funds - didn't do very well but - they were doing that sort of thing and me mother did get help from the - Jewish -
 char - charities.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Jewish people are very good with each other in this way aren't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well I don't know whether they - I think they're perhaps a little better than others. They have organizations you see the - better - off people amongst the Je
ws - and a lot of them who are - have been in England for quite a while - felt it was a duty to look after the - Jewish poor, 'cos there were a lot of poor, and the - there was an organization, there still is, called the Jewish Soup Kitchen. Which was a c
haritable organization - run by some of the better-off people - people like - you know the firm of Cohen }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4589562 &}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  Wilks - well Philip Cohen did a great deal of that - the Marks and Spencers people did quite of - the East, did quite a bit of that. And there were so
me other Jewish families like the man who was the Mayor of Salford, Alderman Finberg. His fam - Samuel Finberg - his family did a great deal of that you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 But was it strictly for Jewish children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 It was for Jewish children - Jewish families g
enerally. And there - there's something else that I used to do to help out - I used to go collecting for the - the Jewish burial society - I used to collect - pennies and tuppences from all the houses in Cheetham.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Were you in it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I wasn't in it - I'm in it - I'm in it now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Were your family in it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No, our family weren't in it. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did they belong to any club at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No, we weren't in any club at all, but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Tell me about the Jewish Burial Society?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 This - there is th
e - the Central Synagogue had a burial board, I think the others may have them to - we're still members because we have been ever since we were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7426541 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  and you pay a fee every week which gives you the privilege of a free burial and perhaps one or two coach
es and a minister to come to the house to attend to things. In other words, relieves you of all the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11168726\charrsid1644444 expense}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  of a funeral. And - this was I think tuppence or threepence a week and there was one man - I don't know how I got this job but he had a number of co
llectors and I was made one of them and it was my job - I used to go all round the Cheetham Hill district and all round the Hightown district and I didn't collect very much in tuppences and three-pennies and I think I got sixpence a day - each time - I go
t sixpence for doing that Sixpence was a fair amount of money you see. Used to spend a Sunday morning doing it. And that was one of me jobs.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Were you expected to go to bed early on schooldays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I think ours was a - a fairly well run family becaus
e - I don't think we had any problem children because the two brothers - one of them who was a problem child was sent to this - orphanage, 'cos he - he was a - I don't think he was very difficult at home but - somebody had to go and he was one - who was c
hosen to go and he ne}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11168726\charrsid1644444 v}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 - he never really got over it. He's been a problem - chap ever since, yes. And he's a man of - getting on for sixty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Who put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Me mother used to put us to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What age did you start putting yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well when we were quite young of course, we were put to bed by our mother when we were - when I was about - oh - of course when I was a boarding school I had a bed of me own but at home - two -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No, there were two of us in 
a bed. I used to sleep with my elder brother and we used to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11168726\charrsid1644444 harmonise}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 . My mother used - used to tell us to stop }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11168726\charrsid1644444 singing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 . We used to sing. Remember one of the songs was - Chocolate Soldier and my brother and I used to sing this while we were in bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How many bedrooms did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Three. I think, yes. And a bathroom. We had a bathroom. But I was going to tell you about the toilet. I can remember the days of the ordinary sanitary toilets when there was no water closets. When we first lived in Therl
mere Street there - were no water closets and it was just a plain border privy with a hole in it and a bin underneath which the men used to come to take through a little door in the entry, pull out and empty and put back again. And whilst we were there wa
ter closest were installed. And - I think until - we went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Great Clowes Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 we had outside toilets. We had a bathroom - it was made out of one of the rooms.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
So your mum and dad would sleep in one room and you boys were divided between the other two?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes. But I never remember much of that because it's going back so long.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How often did you have a bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh once a week - it was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What about clean clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 We used to change once a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Can you tell me where the family had their meals at Therlmere Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Always in the kitchen. These kitchens were biggish kitchen - the room might have been almost as big as this was before the bay was put on, with a sink in one corner. And the family generally lived in that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you eat in any other room on special occasions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No. On - only very rarely - only when there was a - something special on. He very rarely used the other rooms. Only when company came.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Where did your mother cook then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 She cooked in the kit
chen. There was a bit of - there would be a bit of a scullery off this you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did she have a range or did she have gas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 She had an old range to begin with and later on a gas cooker.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Can you tell me what you had for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 And what time it was eaten and who was present?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Yes. Be - before going to school - it would be before going to school - you'd have a piece of bread and jam and tea or perhaps cocoa. That's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 All the family would be present would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
They - yes, generally they were always present. Those that had to go to school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you have anything special on your Sabbath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh yes. Now - Friday night would be a special - Friday night would be the beginning of the Sabbath. When the sun sets on Friday that's when the candles are kindled and if you have wine, you have wine and they -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 And the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Yes, the children's get a sip of the wine and - the - famous meal was a chicken - they used to buy a fowl and this is perhaps somet
hing you'd be interested - the fowls had to to be fowls of good quality without any blemishes. We used to buy them in - you know - Withy Grove, the hen market, bring them home from there and - I would then take them to a slaughter house -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You'd bring them home }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11168726\charrsid1644444 alive}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Bring them home alive, yes, used to tie the feet. And then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You didn't carry them upside down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Not - not while they were alive no. They'd be in a bag - one of these wicker bags you know, alive with their feet tied so they
 couldn't - fly away. We'd take them home and then I would go to the slaughter house, what they call the Showpit, and - I would had in the fowl and he would pluck the feathers away from the neck, lift the neck up and just do that and then he would hand it
 to me and I used to take it to - well, the original ones were primitive, very primitive }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11431234\charrsid1644444 abattoirs}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 , they were nothing more than a - a groove in the flag - in the floor - well you held the chicken or whatever it was until it stopped and all the blood went away, but later on
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How long would it take it to die?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh about ten minutes or so - you held it for about ten minutes and it flapped away you know, and some of the kids were frightened to death to take these live birds.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did the boy always do it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
It was usually the boy. I used to take them up on top of a bus and on one occasion remember going up when somebody's bird flew off the top of the bus. And - oh and the other things - something you'd be interested in. Sometimes - when the fowl was b
rought home after it had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11431234\charrsid1644444 been killed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 - oh I - before I finish let me tell you that later on they had little porcelain blocks in which you could drop the fowl down it would just be held by the - the aperture wasn't big enough for it to go down and you put i
t head first and the blood drained away and it wasn't able to flap about. And that was a bit of an improvement. I don't know what it's like now but I'm talking about many years ago. Then - then we would take them home and we would help me mother to pluck 
t
he feathers. We used to pluck all the feathers off and then they used to get lumps of newspaper and light it and singe it. You know, they used to call them pinkers - the little things come out of the skin. And then the fowl would be - ready - to be attend
e
d to and do you know the Jewish way of opening a fowl? They put it on it's back - they put the fowl on it's back and they split the breastbone and open it out - they don't dry it - draw it. And they take all the innards out, so you've really got nothing m
o
re than the shell. They used to use the neck - we used to cut the head off and they used to use the skin of the neck to make a kind of a sausage, a stuffing with all kinds of breadcrumbs and onions and al which is very, very tasty but very fattening, I do
n
't think it's used very much today. They used to cut the legs off - you know - the feet off and use the legs of course for boiling but what was going on to tell you was that if you opened this fowl out and you found something strange like a pin or a butto
n
 or something like that it was the custom to take the hen to a minister - a rabbi - and he would pronounce whether it was Kosher or not and on a number of occasions it was my job to go and take this hen to the - it had been killed an opened and ready for 
t
he ta - ready for boiling you know, for cooking, and we've had to discard it. We used to give it to the - either somebody might - sometimes came - the washerwoman or a - a maid or something like that or a - somebody who lit the fire for us. We'd give it a
way. Couldn't use it - and we didn't - we didn't use it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Suppose it was a very poor Jewish family?;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 They still didn't use it - they didn't use it. No, they went without.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 This would be your dinner for Sunday - your Sabbath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I would - n
o, it were made for Friday night. For Friday evening and then cold on the Saturday. Then the bits would follow for days afterwards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What did you have for Sabbath breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh I'll tell you what they used to do - they were very fond of frying fi
sh and Friday was a very - popular day for buying - or we may have bought on a Thursday. They used to buy a - lots of fish, hake was very popular in those days. You know, strangely enough they used to look down on people who bought cod. Because - hake was
 very popular, well it was in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Lancashire{\*\xmlclose}
 and amongst the Jewish people, they would buy these hakes and cut them into steaks and fry them or boil them. They would also skin them, take the flesh off and chop them up with onions and - bay leaves and such like 
and make them into little rissoles balls of - and boiled - and boil them with bits of carrot. That was very tasty. In fact - I haven't got them today but had you come yes - tomorrow I would show you some of these things - Friday - I buy them from a local 
shop now, we don't make them anymore because my - we don't do any frying, we go and buy these and for one and sixpence I can get a little - well, it's about that size of this fish - prepared the way I just told you with the skin and bon}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11431234\charrsid1644444 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  round it - you can 
also buy the boiled stuff. And they used to keep that and have it we used to have it sometimes hot and during the Sabbath when you didn't do any cooking, used to have it cold - or cold fried fish, Cold fried fish was a great delicacy amongst Jewish people
.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What type of food did you eat during the week for your ordinary meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh - had quite a lot of meat. You had quite a lot of meat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 About how many times a week would you have meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh eat meat about three or four times a week. As I say, I never -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Any tinned meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No, never used it. No. Because there weren't any Kosher tins in those days. Today there are. None of the big firms - went in for Kosher. We used to have tinned fish - tinned salmon, that would be al right, and tinned
 fruit of course. But - none of the - animal foods, like meat foods were Kosher, not until much later. So nobody ever had those. In fact there was no firm making them until later on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You didn't grow your own fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Or make beer or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No, no, when you said make beer we did make and strangely enough, my son has been doing exactly the same thing in a different way. My mother used to make mead. Mead, yes. With honey, yes. Honey and hops. The mead, yes. M
y mother had a very large earthenware - something like - did you ever see Ali Baba and the Forty Thieves? You know the - crucible that the thieves were in? Small one like that. It must have been about ten gallons or more. And they used to use these for tw
o
 purposes. One was for pickled cucumbers, these small cucumbers about that size - ridge cucumbers they call them - oh much bigger than a gherkin - about that big and we used to pickle these, they were green - you can buy them, they're about that size, you
 
know, round - and these used to be pickled with peppercorns and bay leaves until they were like - like gherkins but much bigger and they used to use 'em for that and we'd have a whole - oh there must have been twenty or thirty or forty in - had so many of
 them. She also used to use this for making mead. And my grandmother was very good at making mead. They used to get hops and honey and sugar and the - and it used to be under the table in the kitchen, this stuff, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11431234\charrsid1644444 fermenting}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  away and the kids used to pinch t
his you know and we had - oh stocks of mead. In fact me mother when - this is much later of of course when I was twenty or getting on for twenty - between sixteen and twenty - she made cherry brandy. From cherries. From cherries and added brandy to it.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did she make wine or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No, she didn't make wine but she may have done but not so much. Strange enough when I mentioned about mead my son started to make wines in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Reading{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 and one of the wines which he's making is mead. But he doesn't use hop
s. Uses honey but not hops. But we made mead with hops. Oh it's made with honey but I'm not so sure it's made with hops because I can remember the - mainly the - the other home made foods that we made was - I don't know whether you're going to have any bu
t there's some double cream }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11431234\charrsid1644444 cheese}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 which I bought but we used to make a sour cheese, like St Ivel cheese but in a much better way. They used to get bowls of milk and used to put it near the fire and wait until the milk got sour. In the old days, I think tod
ay if you have milk that isn't mixed it will go sour without going bad. And when it had gone sour - and - they used to then skim the top off and pour it into a muslin bag, used - oh, used to boil it up and it would go curdey and opour it into a muslin bag
 and hang the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11431234\charrsid1644444 muslin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 bag up and if you went in the kitchen you'd find a muslin bag hung up and it'd have this white curdey cheese inside which is really lovely - Kasse - which is the German word for cheese. Call K}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11431234\charrsid1644444 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 sse.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 It's Kass in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Turkey{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Is it?
 Well it's Kasse in German of course and - Jewish people call it Kass - Kess and smetena. I don't know whether you've heard of smetina. Smettiner is sour cream. In fact we buy it from the Express Dairy - it's not quite the same sour cream but - a very fav
ourite dish, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11431234\charrsid1644444 especially}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 in hot weather was this Kass which is like this cream cheese with this sour cream poured over it and it's a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11431234\charrsid1644444 gorgeous}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  taste. It's made commercially now, we used to make it at a home and it was much better in those days. Really lovely. And baking of course - they did a lot of -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did she bake herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh yes, me mother was very good at baking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What did she bake?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
She baked bread at times. But - Kutchen which is another German word is a very very favourite - and Kuchen
 is really a sweet - a sweetish flavour bread with currants or sultanas in it. And it - as a matter of - we were thinking of getting one for you but - it weren't every - and she used to make that, Kuchen. And pies - a lot of pies, open pies and - you know
,
 the ordinary pies. Exactly the same as anybody else make it. Would get a crust - you'd lay the - roll the stuff out, put it on a plate, put jam and apple or whatever it is, put the top on, press it down the sides and bake it. We did this in a - oh she di
d quite a lot of baking, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Were you allowed to talk during meals?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Could you have what you wanted or did you have to have a bit of everything?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 More or less - well, I don't think we were difficult with our food at all.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Were you allowed to leave anything on the plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
I don't - I don't think they were very strict, I think we cleaned the plate in any case. Some of the children must have been - difficult. I'll tell you something else which is comical - my elder brother
 at one time - got very - cocky and he decided he wanted to eat on his own and he used to clear all the other children out and lock the door and eat his meal by himself while we were on the other side - hanging on the door.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 'Cos - he wouldn't eat with us. Wanted his on his own. He was superior,

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Could you ask for a second helping if you wanted it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh yes. If it was there
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
If you wanted something on the table like the salt did you have to wait until it was passed to you or could you ask somebody to pass it to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well I don't know whether we had salt in - we may have had a cruet - I suppose we did have a cruet but - I'm trying to keep to the early days when things - you see, while - while we were at school and before we we
re at school I was so young that I don't remember a great deal until nine. From nine 'til eleven I was at this boarding school where things were really - rough you see. After that - very soon after we came back from boarding school father died - so things
 
changed very rapidly. We went from Sedgley Park to Strangeways and lived in - very ordinary - very ord - then - well hard from the point of view of - didn't have a lot of money, didn't have a lot of clothes, but we did have - food. We didn't have any holi
days. Never went away on holidays. But had been on holiday before and been to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Blackpool{\*\xmlclose} a few times - when me father was alive, yes. Of course I spent two years at the seaside - at 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Margate{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. After that - from - the time of my fa}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11431234\charrsid1644444 t}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 her}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11431234\charrsid1644444  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 dying - I joined the Jewish Lads Brigade and used to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11431234\charrsid1644444 go to}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 camp, that - my holiday was always in camp. Used to go for ten days to camp. With Jewish Boys Bridgade, yes. In fact I was in the camp when the first world war broke out. We had to break the camp up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Could you bring toys or a book to the table - were they strict about this?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
I don't think so. The children - we weren't terrible strict I don't think. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Could you leave the table when you wanted or did you have to ask?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No, we never had to ask, they would just go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did all the family sit at the table at the same time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes, generally yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Who served the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 My mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Who was served first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
I can't remember my father sitting down to a meal at all - it's beyond all - before my
 time. I was too young you see. But he must have done obviously. Although I think when we were very small we didn't eat with out parents at all. We were fed before - the small children were fed before and didn't eat with their mother and father at all.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You don't know at what age you started to come to the table?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh I think you'd have to be about six or seven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Your mother would feed you somewhere else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Yes. Or the maid would feed us, you see, if we had a maid. They would give the child
ren to eat before because you couldn't rely on them behaving themselves at table when they were very young and the smallest children would be in a chair at the side of the table as well you see. In the way in which people are nowadays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Was your mother an easy person to talk to and did she show affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
My mother had so many children that her affection was different to different ones. I used to get blamed for everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You were the bad boy of the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I wasn't bad boy, no, not th
e bad boy, I wasn't bad, it wasn't anything bad but - I couldn't please my mother any - anything like my elder brother or my other brothers. I had one brother that wasn't very strong. He was supposed to have had something wrong with his heart when he was 
b
orn, but he was so - keen on proving that he was all right he was a very good footballer and a very good cricketer, he died rather young, he was only thirty-seven when he died, but until then he hadn't give - shown much sign but he was a bit of a favourit
e. My elder brother, even - in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7426541 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  life my mother always expected a lot from me.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Was she easy to talk to though - could you share your worries with her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh - well I didn't have much in the way of worries but I - I - used to talk to her a lot 
but it wasn't about worries, it was about old times in Russia and whatnot. She - used to tell me about that. And she used to sing - songs, folk songs, of the times when they were in - Russia and the times when the - pogroms - she was never actually subjec
t
ed to any pogroms but they knew all about it. They weren't in an area which suffered from pogroms although he - I don't know much about the community abroad but - I think my grandmother had a goat or some sort of animal - because she; could milk a goat an
d - milk a cow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Was your father easy to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
I can remember very little of him at all, 'cos when I was young - it wasn't the custom of Jewish fathers to bother much with the children. No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 They didn't seem to have much time
 - there were so many - they didn't have much -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 When your parents came to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}England{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} did they find any prejudice here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
They - yes, there - there was a lot of prejudice, you see, a lot of them were - sort of centred on one or two trades.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 There were a lot in clothing too weren't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
There are a lot in clothing because they'd been tailors and - they - they weren't allowed to go into municipal work at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 The municipal people wouldn't have them. You could never get in - yo
u could never get into a bank. No, not for many years - it wasn't 'til - oh 1920 I should say before - after the first world war I think things were easy but up 'til then the boys who were in a bank - Jewish boy was in a bank was a great rarity and Jewish
 who worked for a corporation was even a bigger rarity I think. There were odd ones.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Were you just allowed an interview and then they made an excuse?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I don't think they ever brought you for an interview. No, no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What other prejudice do you remember meeting as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh - they used to call us sgeebies you know. Sheeny. Have you never heart the word sheeny? Well Sheeny was a - a slang word for Jew and where we lived - you've heard of Magnolia Street haven't you - well I lived almost on
 - on top of Magnolia Street and our street was very much like this. When we lived in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Therlmere Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Therlmere Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} was practically Jewish, but the next street, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Emerson Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 was practically non-Jewish and - they didn't mix a lot. No, they didn't. W
e didn't mix a lot even at school, they used to keep to themselves - although the Jewish children used to take part in non-Jewish activities. They didn't go to church, they used to go to - as I told you - this Band of Hope - because they }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11431234\charrsid1644444 wonted}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  to come to 
the party. They used to have a party and they joined because of the party. We used to go to the parties you see. And the - the children - it was a Church of England school, it belonged to St Johns in Waterloo Road is the church belonging to St Johns schoo
l
 and as far as I can remember there was never any real racial discrimination in the classes. I can't remember any at all. And they would be half and half or even perhaps more one than the other but - we used to have occasional trouble but very little. I'l
l
 tell you what happened once, you might be interested in this - you know the famous - the late Sir Winston Churchill? He was the prospective M.P. of the Exchange Division of Manchester, you probably know that did you? And he came to our - he came to our s
c
hool during the 1908 or 1907 campaign and spoke to us on top of a taxi - to the crowd. He came to our school because he used to have meetings at school. Well the reason why I'm telling you this, that there was a street near us that was composed mainly of 
non-Jewish boys and they used to get balls of paper and tie them with string and come and mob us because they were Conservatives and we were Liberals. Practically all the ordinary Jewish people were Liberal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well they expected better treatme
nt - they got better treatment from the Liberals. The Conservative - the Conservatives were aristocrats and hadn't got much time for poor people anyway and - the - evidently the Jewish people thought they were get - going to get much better treatment from
 
the Liberals. And later on they joined - a lot of them joined the Labour party for the same reason. Because they thought that their chances - as a minority - were going to be a lot better, they would get better treatment and more fairer treatment from the
 Liberals and the Labour people than the - and even today I think that's true - there are plenty of Hewish Conservatives but I think you'll find them in a minority - compared with the others.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did your father vote?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No, they weren't - citizens. The
y weren't - they hadn't got the vote you see. They were foreign - they were foreigners and my father didn't live long enough to be naturalized and me mother didn't - never got naturalized. So they were foreigners. My family - my mother had to report durin
g the war as an alien, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Apart }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11431234\charrsid1644444 from being}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  called Sheenies did you get any other type of prejudice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Never - it was never as severe as that - never as sharp as that. You see, we were almost integrated from 1900 onwards - in Hightown where we liv
ed there were Jews and non-Jews living side by side in many places. So - and as - as I say they used to - sometimes they didn't like the idea of employing these girls to do this - you know, lighting the fires and doing menial work, they thought that was a
 bit degrading because they said the Jewish people ought to do their won dirty work sort of thing you see. And - all the maids weren't Jew - no Jewish maids. No, no. They were all non-Jewish maids.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 And they used to be brought in to light your fire for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
On a Saturday, on a Saturday morning. And on holidays when there was no kindling of fires. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Suppose it was a poor Jewish family and they couldn't afford to bring a maid in to light the fires?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Usually get a boy to do it - a boy wo
uld do - I don't think any of them managed - didn't manage to get something done. Boys used to earn money you know, doing that. Boys used to do it as well - little boys, Jew - non - Christian boys.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Would come in and light the fires for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes
. But I can never remember any serious trouble at all. From the time - 'til the time I lived in Cheetham and in Hightown I can never remember any serious trouble at all. In fact, nothing quite like the 1948 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11431234\charrsid1644444 situation}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  when the British were fighting in Pales
tine and the English soldiers were being, you know, harried by the Israeli's - I - there was a sores spirit then than there ever was in my time that I can remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 In England there was a worse spirit in 1948 you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes. In fact the boys at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Trafford
{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose} one time were thinking of escorting me through {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Broad Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 - they were afraid that I might get attacked in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Broad Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, coming home - in 1948 during the war, the 1948 war with 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Israel{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. The British - the British troops were - and - ant - anta
gonistic towards Israel you see - or the British Army was and there was a lot of - especially along Broad Street and Irwell Street and round there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 But you never experienced any of this as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Not at all. I can never remember any - serious - trouble at all, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You were punished and you got the strap?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Strap - but not - very rare - not very often.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Who punished you - was it your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Father did it. Occasionally me mother did it. Occasionally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Do you remember being punished and what it was for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No, I was punished but I can't remember what it was for. I never did anything really seriously wrong. I was supposed to be a good boy. Yes. Well I did very well at school you see and - good boys at school weren't supposed to do things wrong.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How did your mother bring you up to behave towards your brothers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Towards me brothers? She never mentioned a great deal about that but she used to give me a lot of advice about going out into the world. And I can remember 
and I've repeated it many times, the one thing that she said over and over again, she says, when you go into the world the one thing you must not do is to show somebody up in public. Insult them or - tell things about them, disgrace them in public. She sa
id, they'll never forgive you for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did she teach you to hit back if someone hit you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Yes, she used to say that. If you were hit hit them back. 'Cos you used to come home crying, somebody's hit me, you see. Things like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What do you th
ink she hoped you would grow up to be and what did she think important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well I'll tell you what was a very fond hope of practically all Jewish mothers you know, for their sons, they would marry wealthy girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 There was a - the
re was a tradition - there was a tradition amongst Jewish people that - not only a tradition of wealth as a tradition of education and - a lot of them - were deemed to be aristocrats of knowledge. Not necessarily of manners or anything like that. If you w
e
re an educated person and you were - good enough to become a doctor or a - a lawyer or something like that - then - it used to be considered quite an thing for a - a wealthy man to be glad to had his daughter over even if he was a poor boy because they ha
d this }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11431234\charrsid1644444 aristocracy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 of learning. You see, and if you were clever you're - expected to make a good marriage. I did - I didn't do that but it didn't -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 She just hoped you'd grow up and make a good marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Make a good marriage - in fact they did - 
they did a lot of - they didn't do so much with me - but
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 They had their marriage makers didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh yes, they had what you call the chaperones, yes. Sha}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11431234\charrsid1644444 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 kun. Shatkun. A }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11431234\charrsid1644444 S}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 hatkun is a marriage maker. And it's quite common to come round to a ho
use and say - where the Shatkun knew that the mother had some eligible sons, he'd say, I know a very nice girl who'll - you know - you can be introduced to, and - quite a lot of marriage were made that way you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What did your mother teach you was important }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11431234\charrsid1644444 in life}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh she - we had to be - we had to be respect - respectable, yes. You see, none of my brothers were ever - in trouble through stealing or doing anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You said your father was brought over by refugees?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
You know the travel agent, Fabers. Farbers, well it was the - I think the predecessors to Farbers who did it. They used to act as agents to bring immigrants over.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Was it supported by Jewish people in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Manchester{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Not - not - not to bring them ove
r - once they were over was the - the Jewish Board of Guardians who looked after them and still does.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What did your family think of swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
We didn't swear in our house. No, no, no, they didn't swear. But I ought to qualify that, you see, when you talk about swearing you're thinking in terms of English }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11431234\charrsid1644444 swearwords}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
. But in Yiddish there were words which weren't really course swearing - not - not really coarse but they were - old fashioned swearing like curses and things of that kind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Do you know any of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Do tell me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well I'll have to give it to you in - in Yiddish. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 But you can translate them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh yes, but it's very hard to translate because there - there isn't a - a quick or an easy - translatio
n, for instance, they used to hold their hands up and - and say, oh - woe is me or way is meer, which means woe is me and used to say also, a clot dyon - a clot dyon means a cuse on the years which hasn't got any real significance for English has it.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
But were these English Jewish expressions or were they expressions your mother brought from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Lithuania{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh no, they - they would be from the ghetto's - from the - you know, the continental ghetto's and - and some of them were very comical. Very comica
l indeed, because - this - this word Klag or Klages - German Word Klage - Klog - means a curse, but they would use it in a jocular way, not really spiteful or vengeful or anything like that and - for instance there was a song and - they could get - always
 get a laugh - the Jewish }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11431234\charrsid1644444 comedian}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 were very good at getting a laugh by using these so called curse - swear words in such a way as to make them comical. For instance, in saying - instead of saying a Klogs dyon one of the expressions they used was a Klog to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Columbus{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Now why they should say that nobody really knows, but the combination of the two things was really funny to Jewish people. There's a - there's a man on record I think today - a man called Nickie Katz and he used to do Jewish monologues and things
 like that and one of the expressions that he came out with was a klog Columbus - I think it rhymed with something you see and that would always cause a laugh. But what I'm saying is that the cursing or the searing wasn't really - I wouldn't say it was as
 bad as - spiteful or - coarse as the English form of swearing because it had this sort of Biblical tang to it. Yes, yes. It wasn't considered really - it wasn't considered bad taste really.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Could you join in if older people were talking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Not re
ally. We were - to be seen and not heard was - was the order of the day just as anywhere else you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Do you think you received your ideas on how to behave from both your parents or from one in particular?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes. You - you - I think you got it m
ainly from the mother, you know, the mother is supposed to be the head of the - the Jewish household and played a very important part in the upbringing of the children. In many cases in the past the father was so busy working and so tired that he - he had
 
very little contact with the children and there are cases you know, some of the tailors, they used to tell me this in the old days, they used to finish in the tailors shop on Friday evening and the men used to sit down and play cards 'til Monday morning a
nd not go home at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 All through the Sabbath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
All the way through. They spent all their wages or sometimes they won - they wouldn't even go home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 But I always thought the Jewish people kept up the Sabbath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I'm not saying a lot of peo
ple did but many of them did. Oh - my grandfather wouldn't carry anything if - he had his handkerchief wrapped round his wrist, he wouldn't carry anything in his pocket and he was a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Why wouldn't he carry anything in his pocket?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Because accordi
ng to their interpretation of the - the laws you hadn't got to do any work on the Sabbath and they - interpreted that to mean that you didn't even have to carry anything. I think I've mentioned this before, if anybody had been seen smoking on Stra}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11431234\charrsid1644444 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 geways f
ifty or sixty years ago it was a disgrace you know. Oh yes, nobody - you didn't ever smoke you see - you hadn't got to kindle fire - one of the rules was that should be no kindling of fires, that's why the young - non - Jewish children used to come and li
g
ht fires because of the kindling you see, and I think I also mentioned that some of the families who were - I suppose if they had the means - used to have a samavar which was burning - lit on a Friday afternoon and kept right through 'til Saturday night w
h
ile they can just brew the tea just as - without having to touch the light. Oh - only one family that did that - I don't think it occurs today. Probably not. But I used to go to one family that used to do this, it would - I was always interested in these 
s
amavar because they drank a lot of Russian tea, they were sort of glasses of tea with lemon in it you know and they used to get hold of a piece of sugar, I don't know whether you've ever seen them do it have you - they hold the sugar in their mouth and th
ey kept the block of sugar, you know, the lump sugar while they sang - drank the tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 So they drank through the sugar?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Through the sugar, yes. Have you ever seen that? Oh yes, they always - used to have a slice of lemon - hot water and lemon and - I suppose it was tea but it was very very weak and they used to suck this block of - sugar, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Our Saturday would the equivalent of you Fridays and our Sundays the equivalent of your Saturdays?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No, it's not quite like that. You see, th
e Jewish Sabbath comes in at Sundown on Friday night, so it actually starts from sunset on Friday and goes on 'til sunset on Saturday. So -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Tell me what you did on the Sabbath - did you have different clothes and dress up and go to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well 
- well, yes, because as a boy - as a boy I was a member of the North Manchester Synagogue Choir. You see, in order to earn a little bit of money, boys who had anything of a voice - used to join the choir and it was always a - an all male choir. There were
 no girls in it, only boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Why only boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well that - because you couldn't have the girls mixed in with the men - they're separated you see in a synagogue so if they have the reading desk, which is the centre of the synagogue and the canter the 
singer on - on the reading desk with - with all his documents and his scrolls he had his choir round him and you couldn't have - he couldn't have girls there. So they - and there were never any girls choir. Even today - there are -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Why were they kept separate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh that's the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11431234\charrsid1644444 custom}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
. The men and women don't - co-habit in the synagogue at all. Except - in the - in their home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 It's not that the women distract the men?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I doubt that very much. I don't think distraction had anything to do wit
h it - I think it's largely - oh - I suppose in the old days women weren't considered as important as men you know, they took - they took - they took no part in religious service at all. The only part they played - if at all - was in the home. They kept u
p
 the kosher house, what they call a kosher house and looked after the dietry lawas and also did what was necessary for any little celebration they had in the house. But apart from that they never even encouraged the girls to go to the synagogue until late
ly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did your mother and father go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
They went mainly on - the New Year and the Black Fast - what we call the Black Fast. Practically all the Jews went on those days - but - as - as a boy as I say I was a member of this choir but not only that, when we lived in - Great Clowes Street we all -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Was this after your father died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
This was after my father died, yes. Before I'd be - I would be too young you see and - and they were con - they weren't worried about children of nine and ten, they di
dn't care very much although some parents took them - and they do today, but they weren't as concerned until the boys were of such as age as to start leaning for their confirmation. Then - they -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 This is thirteen is it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I went to - I went to a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11431234\charrsid1644444 Hebrew}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 school - went to a Hebrew school from the age of about eight or nine - seven or eight but - until you approached thirteen - so it would be oh perhaps a year before - they wouldn't be as keen as they would later on you see because - the importance of 
being trained for your confirmation which is - goes by the name of Balmetza, I don't know whether you've heard of the term. Well that's very important }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 amongst}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  the Jews because then a Jewish boy becomes a man to all intents and purposes as far as religion is concerned.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Tell me about your religion generally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Tell me about the ceremonies - the lighting of the candles you told me about?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well - yes, well what they do it, they have a special loaf that - and if you notice or if you may 
notice that the loaf is made in certain way that it's - how shall I describe it, not like a cottage loaf - it's a bulky loaf with little knobs on it. And - and the idea so you can break it, you didn't have to cut it even you see. And - that's I suppose th
e origin of breaking of bread. These loaves are kneaded - I know you must have seen them - they're - they're sort of oval shaped and they're all little - little knobs on them. Well - those - those were called halla - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}
}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}halle{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Halle{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} is the bread which was used
 - on Friday night, and they put it on the table and cover it with a cloth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Your mother would do this would she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh yes, she would do that. And then the idea is that that's prepared and the candles are there and just b - as the Sabbath comes in 
the - wife would say a little prayer and kindle the lights and prepare if they have it, a bottle of wine and some glasses so that when the father came back from the synagogue he would say a small prayer to celebrate the coming of the Sabbath and drink the
 wine and pass it round to the children. Now we did that when we were very young but - my father was away very often on a Sabbath so it just lapsed and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 But you did have family prayers always did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well it wasn't really a prayer, it was only just a blessing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did Jewish people say grace at table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh yes. When I was at the boarding school it was a great feature, each boy in turn, took - it was a great honour - he said the grace after - the grace before meal is a very short one, it - b
lessed art thou o Lord our God who - something to do with the fruit of the ground, it's a very simple prayer you see. But the prayer after the meal is a long prayer and each boy had to learn this and it was his duty or his honour - one day - perhaps once 
a
 fortnight or perhaps once a month and he would have to learn it because he would have to recite it on his own. When I was at boarding school, yes. Now that only occurred at a wedding or some other kind of function when the minister makes a very big play 
of the grace after meals and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 its}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
' sung with great gusto, especially the parts that everybody knows and - you're not supposed to smoke until that's - all been said. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 So really the Sabbath would be taken up with just going to the synagogue?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I w
ent to the synagogue a lot because after a death the boys are expected to say a prayer three times a day for eleven months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Tell me about a Jewish funeral - that's totally different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes. Well I can tell you about a Jewish funeral. The - the - t
he Jewish people don't make a great deal of ceremony about a - a person who dies because a dead body is supposed to be unclean. Oh yes. It's - well of course there's no life in it so they treat it as unclean. And what happens, if a person dies they then c
all in the burial board. Now, we - my wife and I - have been members of the Central Synagogue Burial Board since the day we were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7426541 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  and we paid a - I told you I used to go and collect for this thing - well now I pay every half year and it's gone up fro
m a penny or tupence a week to more like two shillings a week, but - that's only by the way. But if you are a member and its best to speak of people that are otherwise there's a lot of difficulty of those paupers - I don't know what happens in the case of
 those that have never contributed, there must be some means but I don't know about that, but - if you are a member of the burial boards you then }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 notify}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  the beadle or the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 This is before 1918 you're talking about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh - it's - today its not chang
ed. Not changed. No, it's all the same. No change.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Do you remember a funeral in the family - you'd remember your father's wouldn't you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I've been to a lot of funerals.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Prior to 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well of course. Not only - not only that as a - a 
boy bugle in the Jewish Lads Brigade I used to go to war victims and blow the last post over them - if they happened to die in England.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Tell me about a funeral in particular before 1918.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes, I will tell you about - yes, I don't think there's an
y change really, no, no. None at all really. This - this board is notified and they send the undertaker and the undertaker comes to the house and - they take the body into some room - 'cos the body has to be washed and fitted with a - a shroud covering an
d - they always bury them very quickly after they - die.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Even in a cold district?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Any time - any time, but the - I'm speaking now of the Orthodox - which is ninety-nine per cent of them, because many of the Reform Jews still would be buried accor
ding to Orthodox methods - cremation is very very unusual, somebody being cremated today by the way - Doctor Mills, but that's very unusual. And what happens is this person is called in and he prepares the body or tells his assistants to prepare the body,
 measure it for a coffin. And - what I was going to say - that if a person died at say nine o'clock in the morning they could be buried at half past three the same day. Yes. They very rarely -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Is it always the same day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Always the same - if they 
can do it. Except if they happen to die late on a Friday afternoon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Then what happens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
They don't bury anybody on Sat - on the Sabbath you see. In fact you can't get in touch with the ministers on the Sabath - they won't hear of it. They won't have anything to do with it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What kind of clothes do you wear?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh yes, I'll tell you what - I'll just tell you the story of the - the - the customs. The - body is laid out in a separate room and there are women - special women - who do the job of
 preparing the body, washing it, dressing it up in shroud and - or a covering and also - staying over night with it with candles - they put candles round the body and there'll be watchers - people who will watch over night, if they have to keep them over 
night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What is the theory of the watch?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
I suppose it's an ancient custom that nobody will steal the body I suppose. That's the only thing I can think of. Because as children, and even as a grown-up, you - you may go in but you're not usually in t
he house unless it's somebody very close to you - into the room, because you wouldn't go in at night but they are in this room with the women who watch. Sometimes I think there are men who watch to - men who do that for a - sort of a - small fee - they're
 sort of professionals. And - assume that a person dies in the afternoon and they're not going to be buried on that same day - the coffin is then made and the coffin is the simplest possible - it's made of plain unvarnished wood -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 It's not as elaborate as most?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Not elaborate in any way and it has rope handles. It hasn't got any decoration of any kind - it's a plain straightforward shaped coffin of course in wood with rope handles and the - the idea of course of all undertakers is to make sure the 
body is in position it could be put into the coffin, 'cos if a person is bend they have to move them before rigormortix sets in and put them right, and then - what happens then is that when the time comes for the funeral to start they will have the body e
i
ther on chairs on a - in the coffin - they lay it in a coffin - bring the coffin along, put the body in and leave the top - not - covered - not screwed down you see and then when they're ready the close relatives, those of the immediate family then come i
n
to the room and stand round the - coffin and the minister then forms - something which is equivalent to renting of the clothes and you normally put a - an old garment on because they snip the garment. If it was a waistcoat they'd probably - I've got pullo
v
ers that are cut over here you see, or a waistcoat which is cut over there and women they cut the garments somewhere and that's only done - daughters or sons would have this done, a sister or a brother would have it done and of course a father or mother i
f it was a child but only the closest blood relations.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What is the symbolism of this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
That's to symbolize the Biblical - custom of rending the clothes - yes. I don't know about sprinkling with ashes. I don't think - I think that's been discontin
ued but the - the cutting of the garment is still done. And 1st one I went to my wife's - sister died and when my brother died they cut my clothes. My brother died about ten years ago.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Then you would go off to the cemetery?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Then - then - the bod
y would then be carried out to the hearse - the hearse and the hearse is a completely enclosed hearse - it's black, there are no windows and - they also had lamps at the side to symbolize candles. And it's a - it's a very }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 sombre}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  looking thing because - as I say, all black.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 This is the custom as before 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 It's the same today - it hasn't changed - the hearses must be more }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 modernised}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 - 'cos they had horses at one time. Oh I've seen them with horses, yes. Long time ago. And the other custom is tha
t the women do not follow the coffin and go to the cemetery. Women don't go on the cemetery. Not the relations - no, some women go who are not related but - not the women of the family don't go. I think that was - it may have been done elsewhere on the Co
ntinent and that but I think they used to cry so bitterly and create so much noise that - coming to England and it would be such a strange custom to have women crying }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 behind}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  - a hearse that they discontinued that and the women don't go - well our women neve
r went to any of the funerals at all. Now then, when they get to the cemetery they all assemble in a small room. This room - is - it's not - it must be about four or five times as big as this with - chairs - chairs or seats all the way round and the - nea
rest relation - male relations they would be are just seated on one side of the room and - there are men - there are certain men, generally members of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 trade
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  of Levi who have the - it's an honour or a custom, because they were the descendants of the prie
st and they undo the - shoes - and undo some of the garments of the bereaved which is another sort of custom, symbolic of the rending of the garments you see and they say certain prayers, there's a form of prayer for a funeral said, in this hall before th
e
 body is laid to rest you see. And then you come in at one end of the room, the doors - has large doors at both ends - you come in at one - you don't go out the same way, you go forward into the cemetery and the trestle which is a very simple wooden trest
le, it's a sort of a - an open bench with handles on - four handles and the men carry this and it's covered - as a rule the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 coffin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  is covered with a - a blue velvet cloth with the shield of David on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Does blue have any significance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 It's a - a tr
aditional Jewish colour. The Hebrew - the Israeli flag is blue and white and pale blue is very favourite colour. Royal blue. Pale blue and royal blue and - and the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You'd remember your own father's funeral wouldn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You were about twelve when your father died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Ye, yes, yes. Now at the - when they get to the - grave the grave of all the Jewish people - of Orthodox Jewish people is a separate grave for everybody and it's dug to a depth of six feet and they don't put bodies one 
on top of the other. There's not such thing as a - a family vault. For instance, if a - a wife dies and she wants the husband to be - buried near her they'd have a double grave, they'd use one side and you can see them with a headstone that covers the two
 
ready for the next person and they - then - all gather round the grave and the minister stands at the head of the - you know - the grave with the relatives at the side and then he says other prayers and the - the prayers at a funeral are very similar to t
he Christian prayers, dust to dust. Yes. And a lot of it is bound up in the mourners should not mourn for ever and - days }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 will}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  pass and they should think of all the - good things for the person who's passed, and then they lower the - coffin into the grave a
nd it goes down and then the closest relations then cover the - body with soil with the back of a spade.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Why the back of a spade?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Now I don't know - I can't - I don't know the significance of the back of the spade. It may be - an old custom. Al
ways the back of a spade. And not only the relative but almost anybody who wishes can go and stand round the side of the grave and throw earth, it's supposed to be an honour to the dead for a person to help to cover - to put the earth over them. And then 
w
hen the earth is covered they then go back into this room and they say another prayer, they usually say the afternoon service, you know, the afternoon prayer, and at each time from them own the close - the closest male relation recite the prayer for the d
ead - what they call the kaddish and the kaddish is a traditional prayer said by all mourners.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How often is this said?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 This is said - oh sometimes two and three times at a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 service}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  and it's said three times a day for the next eleven months and the
n once a year after that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Who would do it in your family when your father died - the elder brother?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh me elder brother and me and my younger brother, yes. Yes, I had to go to the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 synagogue}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 . Used to get up in the morning, that's how I came to go
 in the choir, I went to this synagogue - they have - in a synagogue they have a - like you would have a small chapel they'd have a - called a Bas'hem Middrash or Bethem Middrash which is the sa}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 v}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 adi way of saying which is the house where the laws the - doc
uments of the law are read, it's a sort of an }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 abject}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 of the synagogue - it isn't a synagogue but they do hold prayer meetings there. It's usually a smaller room where small congregation, because they don't want to use the large synagogue you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 We would have the equivalent in the Lady chapel wouldn't we?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
You would have something similar to that. But it would be - either uneconomic or too cold or would be uncomfortable to have a huge church with only about two or three people in it so they had this smaller one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 And you had to go there as boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
We had to go - and every congregation that has this must include ten males over the age of thirteen - what is called a minion and a mimmion means that - unless that number of males is there then 
the - kaddish cannot be repeated and what happens you - it doesn't happen of course at a cemetery as a rule because there are plenty there but when the family come back they then stay in the house for what they call the Shiba which is seven days of }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 moruning}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 when they not - they don't sit on ordinary stools - on a chair, they sit on low stools. They don't shave, in fact they go un - without shaving men do for about a month, you may see some men about with a - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 a growth}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  and you'll know that - you may know, gue
ss that they're in mourning. And they don't go out of the house and people will come into the house and all the mirrors are covered with cloth - either turn them to the wall or they cover them; because you don't look in a mirror and - it's supposed to be 
good - neighbourliness to visit a house of moruning and they generally take something sweet, either a cake or sweets or chocolate, give them to the mourners but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Is this a new tradition?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No. No, this is still today when - their sister died about
 two or three years ago next door we went through all this in the ordinary way and they would - happen somebody died tomorrow it would be held in exactly the same way and the minister from the congregation, if you belonged to a congregation, would visit a
nd will carry on the service. It depends }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 how}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 Orthodox or how devoted the - relatives, the mourners are. I some cases they will go on having a service in the house three times a day or twice a day for seven days. They won't hold it on the Sabbath. Never on a
 Friday night and it wouldn't be held if it was one of the holy days like the New Year or the Feast of the Tabernacles - any time where there's a holy day when people go to the synagogue they don't have the service, they break off and start again you see.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Which is your most holy day - what is the equivalent of our Christmas Day?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
The most - well there's no equivalent of course but the most holy day in the Jewish }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 calendar}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  is the day of Atonement.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What did you do as a child on the Day of Atonement?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 The Day of Atonement.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Can you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh yes, very very very clearly. You see, as I said earlier the New Year, which is round about September and - you see - the Jewish }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 calendar}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  is a regular - lunar calendar, every month has twenty
-eight days so there are thirteen months in a - in a year and it goes by the new moon. The new moon is called Roush Parish - the head of the month. Hadish is a month and Roush is - so if you have a new moon you know that's the beginning of the Jewish mont
h
. And they had these, as I say, thirteen a year because it's quite regular and - on the first of Tissury which is the month in which the New Year falls - the year begins on the month of Tiddury and the first and second of Tissury are held as New Year - th
en there are ten days of penitence culminating in the Day of Atonement which is a very very important day, in between people are supposed to - well I suppose they would what call shrine themselves - prepare themselves for this day of atonement.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Do you remember your parents doing this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh yes, they all did this.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Tell me what they did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
What they did was, if they had the time they would go to a lake and sit at the side of a lake and recite certain prayers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How would they be able to do this in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
Salford{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well go to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Broughton{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} or - oh yes, they would sit there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Then it would be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 full}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  of Jewish people at the Day of Atonement?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Not full. No, no, and not the Day of Atonement - this is in between. They're preparing themselve
s. You might find them on the Day of Atonement but not usually. And then when the Day of Atonement comes it syarts off in the evening with the very famous KOLNIDRI - you may have heard of the KOLNIDRI. It is a - a very famous prayer - well when I say famo
u
s, very well known prayer - and - it really means that all sins are remitted - the whole idea is that you prepare yourself and you admit to all your sins so that you should be given remittance of your sins and - penitence and charity and righteousness are
 
the things which you should strive for because they will give you - if you do that then you will be cleared of your sins and - this as I say is a most holy day and - most Jewish people, when I say most I a larger percentage of both males and females, not 
so much the females but the males certainly, will start a fast and it will be a complete fast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you do this as a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh yes. I - I - do it as a boy. I did it last year and the year before for about twenty-six hours.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 But as a boy you did it with your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh yes. If you were young - if you were quite young they would allow you to break a fast - children, they can't - children - fasting all day. They would fast from the evening until perhaps midday the next day - even small children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You did this as a child did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh yes, I fasted until midday. And when I was a boy I fasted a whole - but sometimes long -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Do you remember your mother and father going to the Lake in Broughton Park?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No, they didn't do
 it but old men did. Old Jewish men did. Nor - Orthodox and more devoted people. We had a friend who used to do it regularly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
What other activities did they have in the synagogue - did you have social activities at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh yes, very much so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What type of activities?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Did they have a Sunday school or anything - I know you went to church of England as well at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Enys Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - you traitor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Yes. But - I'm not a traitor at all, no, I didn't actually go to the Sunday school you
 know. No. I said earlier that I went to the Band of Hope as a boy but the Sunday school was - the Eny's Street Sunday school, I was a member of their band there, I didn't go to Sunday school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You went to the Eny's Street Band of Hope then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No, 
not the Eny's Street Band of Hope, it was the Eny's Street band. I was a member of the school band.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 But you were also a member of the Band of Hope?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No, the Band of Hope was when I was a small child.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What was this and where was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Wel
l the Band of Hope was really nothing more than a promise, you got a small certificate and a promise that you wouldn't smoke or drink until you were twenty-one and - you paid, I think fourpence it was - something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Where did you attend that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 At St Johns school - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}St Johns{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, Cheetham - my first school. And because the other children - the non-Jewish children joined, we joined. They didn't object.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
You'd get no religious instruction at all at school would you - you'd just come out when the prayers were on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
In some cases not even that - if they had communal prayers the Jewish children used to stand with the others and just do nothing - just stand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Weren't you allowed to withdraw at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Not until later on. Not 'til later on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How did your parents feel about this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Nothing - no they didn't worry, some did. Some did. And those that object wouldn't sent their children to a church school. They'd send them to a Jewish school.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Were there a lot of Jewish schools round here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh yes, Waterloo Road school, Southhall street - - they were all Jewish but they had a predominance of Jewish children but the Jews school was a Jewish school and there they had Jewish religious - well not }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 services}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  but observances duri
ng the school and they had Hebrew as part of the curriculum you see. But in the other schools because there were so many Jewish children they would be - I suppose as a concession to the Jewish children - they would have - separate Jewish prayers. You see,
 
before 1944 there was no common form of prayer for schools. When Butler brought the Education Act in one of the - principle things was the common form of prayer wasn't it, so that almost anybody could - conform to it and I think with the exception of the 
Catholics there's never been any trouble because - it - it more or less non-}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 denominational}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  isn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What age did you start school - do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Four. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you go for the full day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh yes, a whole day. Do you remember me telli
ng you that I refused to go to school when I should have done and hid under a bed and had to bring -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Which school did you go to first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 St Johns. Yes, yes. I went until I was nine - nearly nine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you stay the full day there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What time did you finish?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well we used to go at nine - nine 'til twelve and two 'til four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Was it boys and girls mixed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
In the smaller classes - the lower classes, yes. I think the whole of the - the whole of the school was mixed - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Who went with you - did you go alone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh no, it was only just down the street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you come home to lunch?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh yes. We had two hours. There were no - there were no school meals then -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What did you think of it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Of the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 As a Jewish boy going into a Church of England school tell me how it felt?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Was nothing at all - it didn't seem - no, because you were in the company of many other Jewish children. It wasn't a - an exception you know. I should say that about
 thirty or forty percent of the children at St Jonns were Jewish. There were no Jewish teachers - there were no Jewish teachers that I remember. But of course there'd be other schools at - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Waterloo Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} school and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Southhall Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, there were many Jewish t
eachers, oh yes. The ladies next door were in fact one of the teachers there. She - she taught at St Lukes which is a Church of England school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How did you like the teachers?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Very much indeed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Were there any special things they taught you about cleanliness or punctuality?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No. What they emphasised, and I can remember this very clearly, that we used to march up from the - playground up to our - classrooms and if you didn't behave yourself I've been clouted - by the master - right across me ear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Was that always the form of punishment you got?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 The cane, yes, and a strap.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Do you remember what you got it for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh well, bad work or misbehaving. Not paying attention.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did the girls get it as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I don't remembe
r the girls getting hit but I certainly had the cane many a time. Oh yes. Either be wandering - my mind'd be wandering although I was pretty good at school you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Were your parents interested in your schoolwork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh yes. They - they -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did they ever attend school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No, my parents never attended school. But my - one of my aunts attended a night school, you see, for immigrants, even in those days they encouraged them to learn English and I think me mother went about twice to a night scho
ol to learn to read and write - I think she only went twice but one of my aunts did go and eventually I think learnt to read and write - reasonably well. A few of them did go. Now the lady next door who died a couple of years ago, she went to night school
 for a bit. As I say, they encouraged them because they wanted them to be able to speak. And it - all this teaching of immigrants and that is nothing new you know, it's been going on - no, it's been going on in England for seventy-eighty years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did either your mother or dad read out aloud or did you have to read to them?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh I never read to them. But - my mother - had a fund of Jewish stories and Jewish songs and a lot of them were rather sad ones because of the pogroms although I've told you that 
our family and RLussia never actually suffered from the pogrom, they'd heard quite a lot about them and knew the songs that the - people in the ghetto used to sing about pogroms and - my mother used - used to sing them to me, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did anyone play an instrument in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh later on we all played instruments.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you have musical evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh much - much later than 1918 - not before 1918. Only before 1918 when I was a bugler, I used to stand on the roof of our outside loo and blow 
the bugle into the brickfield because they wouldn't let me play anywhere else. That's where - that's where I practiced. All the kids used to come round to watch me. This was when I lived in - you know - Cheetham - about 1955-1916.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 When you had a birthday was it any different at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you have anything special on a Jewish birthday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Not really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you have parties or guests?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
They did have parties but - we didn't do much about birthdays at all. That came very much late
r in life and in the - the older - the newer generations but in our family - our particular family never celebrated much in the way of - not even twenty - not even twenty-first birthdays - it wasn't the custom to do that at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you have birthday presents though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
We got presents but I don't think they were birthday presents. We never - made a fuss of birthdays at all. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did your parents ever play games with you or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No. Not that I can remember, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you have a lot of books, newspapers and magazines in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No. We had comics. Comics. I used to be given - I think - Saturday - oh well - if I'm talking about the - boarding school days I had a right - a high old time 'cos I got ninepence a week. Ar
e you interested in that? You see - the period of my life is so varied, at one we had practically nothing but food and the other time - lived like a lord in flannels during the summer at boarding school with ninepence a week pocket money which was a lot o
f money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What boarding school did you go to and what age were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Margate Jewish College. I went from 1909 to 1911.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How old were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I was just over nine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 But until then you'd gone to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}St johns{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh - until then I'd been at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}St Johns{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, that was the only school I'd been to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Tell me about boarding school - did you like it and the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh mar - marvellous. Marvellous. My wife's brother was with us at the - at school and his - his name, I often tell of this, he was 
a very good - athlete - he's dead now, and his name was Abrahm Glass and he was called Abe Glass and we had a master who used to turn his name backwards and tease him and he used to say, it's Eager Selb again - if he was doing something wrong it'd be Eage
r
 Selb again and it became a password. But what I remember mostly about the boarding school was that we had all these fads, with our pocket money all the boys would either buy mouth organs one week or they would buy water pistols or they would buy some oth
e
r - and it - oh half the boys would buy them and go round shooting at each other and all the rest of it but the one thing I remember very clearly, I used to go with another boy to - and this boy by the way, he's dead now - he's a very well known Salford f
a
mily. Do you know the firm of Lande's who used to be in Cheetham Hill - in Regent - Road? Well I went to this school with - well he - he - he became Jack Landes but Julius Lande - the second son of Mr Landes who had the shop there you know, well Julius or
 
Jack as he was called later, was friendly with me at school. In fact we met the family before we went to this school, I remember going to Landes many many years ago. When I was only about nine I went with me father and me mother and we had tea with Mr and
 Mrs Lande.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You went shopping there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No, no, we went to visit them because they were sending their boy and they had a little - I think they had rooms at the back of that shop in Regent Road, 'cos it was a fairly small shop then, it became - very 
big didn't it. But he was - he was a German - of German extraction Mr Lande and they had this - it was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 fairly}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  large shop and they lived at the back and because they knew that we were going to this boarding school we were invited there and I remember goin
g there to tea. But what I was going on to tell you was that Jack Laned - Jack and I - he used to get his pocket money - we use to line up on a Friday afternoon after lunch and get our pocket money. Then we were free until the Sabbath came in and we used 
to -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 To go back to the boarding school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh yes, I was going to tell you what happened after we had - got our pocket money. Yes, well we used to line up just after we'd had our lunch at Saturday - you know - after midday. And then we were given, 
as I say, I was given ninepence. Now my younger brother got sixpence and my elder brother got a shilling which was quite a lot of money in 1909 as you can imagine. I had ninepence. With this ninepence I used to go with Jack Lande and I went quite often to
 a - a bakers shop in the town in Hargate - Cliftonville this was - and buy thirty-one rock cakes for sixpence.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What did you do with thirty-one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Wait a minute. We used to get a huge back and we counted these thirty-one - they were only small you 
know - little rock cakes you know the rock - something like mince pies you get but they had currants in and we'd eat a few of them there and then and we used to take them in the dormitory and - on one occasion the fleet came into Margate Harbour and - we 
- our dormitory was on the front on the Cliftonville parade - the front and at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 night-time}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  the fleet used to have these searchlights and they used to rake all of the front with the searchlights you see. And they used to shine into our dormitory and they thou
ght they were looking at us you know. We used to stand on our beds and dance and - get these cakes and start eating them and showing them to the - to the sailors because - the silhouettes on the back of the room - the light used to throw a silhouette of t
he children dancing and we used to have great laughs in the dormitory.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What were the teachers like and how did they treat you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well they were very good the teachers. They were resident teachers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How many lessons a day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh we'd have norm - normal lessons because children were prepared for the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}college{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Procesptors{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. The - instead of the G.C.E. or whatever it is goday there was in the South of England different levels of examination by the - what they call the College of Proceptors and there were different grades and we were prepared for these grades.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What time would you start in the morning here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh we'd start at nine o'clock in the ordinary way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You'd get up and have breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 We'd have a full - a full day, we had breakfast, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 About what time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh it'd be about eight o'clock. And then - we - we'd have - I think we started off with prayers - about nine o'clock. Jewish prayers, yes. And then we'd have normal lessons until midday - then we'd have lunch.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What would you have for lunch - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 Jewish}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 food}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh a meal - oh - no, there wasn't - there was nothing particularly special about the food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Not even kosher food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh, it was kosher of course, but what I'm saying is it would be typicall
y English food because there I learnt to hate cabbage. Yes. Now they used to have different dishes and as you can imagine children like certain dishes. Meat pie was a very special occasion, we all loved the meat pie, but as we were amongst the smaller boy
s
 we were served at the last and quite often we never got any meat pie - there wasn't any left. And - we were also dished - we had quite a lot of cabbage. I learnt all the regular meals, there was nothing special about those meals, you'd have exactly the s
ame meals in the school today or even in the home. Meat and veg - two vegetables in the ordinary way with a pudding to follow. Except they wouldn't have a meat dish to follow - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 to precede}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  a milk dish. We didn't do that. Don't have meat and milk together. An
d if it was a milk dish, oh we had there was nothing special about the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 foods}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 , we had rice pudding when the time came, we'd have soup, we'd have chicken, we'd have meat. I don't know if we had any chips but we certainly had these - meat pies which we loved.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What about breakfast in boarding school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well quite - quite normal - you have egg - fried egg and - oh, we'd have fried eggs, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 So it was a very good boarding school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh a very good boarding school. We were fed very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What about tea meals in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh you'd have - kippers, fish, all kinds. I don't think the - there's any real change about the type of food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
What about the discipline in those days when you were a boy - you hear about boarding school discipline being very tough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
In our school it was very good. But - I could tell you about me brothers school 'cos I told you earlier two of my brothers went to this - orphans school in London - in Norwood when one of them barred - barred the masters out - he
 had a barring out. He looked the masters out, yes. I don't remember much about it because I was young at the time and he was a long way away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 But they had a bad time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 Oh yes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 , has got a bad reputation, one of my brothers. He lives in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} now 
and - he barred the masters out. He started a revolution at the school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Because conditions were so bad?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Yes, they were treated bad - well I won't say they were treated badly but they were treated like orphans are treated. But that's very exceptional.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 This was a Jewish school was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh yes. And strangely enough, the headmaster of that school in later life, I used to visit them because he was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7426541 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  to my wife's cousin and he was always a bit -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You mean the punishment was very bad at this school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well, I don't know whether the - I don't really know a great deal about it - all that I know, what I was told - they didn't tell me in any detail but he led a barring out at the school because they were dissatisfied with what was going on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What about punishment at your school - was that good?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
I don't ever remember get - getting punished. Not at all, no. I was a pretty good child you know - conformer, I always conformed very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What was the difference of things they 
emphasised here at a Jewish school after being at St Johns?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh very little - practically -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What did they emphasise as important in life do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well I suppose behave yourself and - you know - say your prayers. We said our prayers regularly at this boarding school because the - the headmaster was a Reverend - he was a minister. He - he ran the school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 He would be a Rabbi you mean?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
He wasn't a Rabbi, no, but he was a minister. There is a difference between a minister of religion and a Rabbi. A Rabbi is a slightly higher grade of minister; who was recognised by the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 Rabbinical}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 college. These other people would be recognised as ministers of religion but they'd have no special qualifications. But a Rabbi has special qualifications because he is a - a man of - of learning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How long were the intervals between coming home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh they - remember I told you that one - on one particular year - we were only there two years - but on one particular year me mother come to Margate and stayed for six weeks - I think I told you that didn't I. Instead of us going -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 She came and stayed at the best hotel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
I wouldn't say it was the best hotel but it was nice hotel - was Ricardo's near the fort - it was nice hotel 'cos I can re
member it - strange how things come back - that was my first introduction to Robertson's Silver Shred marmalade. And that was just outside the famous - bandstand called the Fort at Margate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Why did she come down - to see how you were going on?
