es, instead of all three of us coming back to Manchester which she wouldn't know what to do with us for six weeks she came to - Margate and stayed - through the summer and we had the most }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 marvellous}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 First of all you went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}St Johns{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}St Johns{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Then you went onto - you were at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}St Johns{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} from four?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 From four until nearly nine I should say, round about nine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Then at nine you went to the boarding school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Nine I went to the boarding school and came back just abo
ut eleven - before I was eleven. Then my father died in the December of 1911. Then - I went to the Cheetham Central school, it was called the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}High{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Grade school{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. In {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Heath Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} in - off {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}
}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Cheetham Hill Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, do you know it all all - Cheetham Central school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Then you went on to Manchester Grammar didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Then I went to the Grammar school from there, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Can you give me any sort of contrast between the schools - just generally?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes. The - now at the - the first school, the primary sch
ool I did extremely well. I was a - I think I was an exemp - an exemplary pupil not only by -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Were they all children of the same type of background at 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}St Johns{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh yes, yes, yes. There weren't - there weren't any particularly poor children. Beca
use - because close to St Johns wasn't exactly a slum - it wasn't a slum. It was - a shade better than a slum and there were people who were in regular work and they perhaps - small tailors and perhaps shopkeepers and - market people and things like that.
 
They weren't labourers. You see the Jewish people - very few of them ever became labourers - they weren't allowed or they weren't particularly fit for it. Then of course there's the difficulty of the Sabbath - they didn't want to work on the Sabbath but -
 
the families that lived round Therlmere Street which was so close to the school you see Helm Street where St Johns was oh and there was Herbert Street running in between then there was Therlmere Street and I think I was no further from the school then fro
m here to the end of that block there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 So they'd all be form a similar background?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh very similar, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you ever get gangs or groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh yes. I think I already mentioned that we - one of our favourite games was to play in what we called the double entry, the back of the - that was very close to the church - St Johns church, did I tell you? Well there was a - a row of houses on 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Waterloo Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} which was - adjacent to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}St Johns{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} church. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}St Johns{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} church - do you know it at all? {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}St Johns
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} 
church - next to Cheetham's cricket ground. Well the street along there I think is Bridoak Street and from Bridoak Street to Bignor Street was a row of fairly big houses and then behind that there was a - different houses - was what we called the double e
n
try, instead of being an ordinary straightforward back entry it had a - a bend in it and two of them ran together for some reason or other and it was our favourite playing ground because we used to jump from wall to wall in the entry, the boys did. In fac
t, her brother, my wife's brother had a serious illness as a result of falling when he was jumping.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 And you used to do this in gangs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
We did this in gangs - were small gangs and it was our favourite game to play rallyo and all the rest of it - you know the games that boys play and chase round the double entry and also get chased by the - grown-ups as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Were there any children left out at your school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Left out - how do you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Do you notice children who were always left out - 
perhaps the teachers treated them differently to other people or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No, but we used to play in the school playground, we used to have a game called rally-o, I don't know if you ever remember rally-o. There's somebody would be in a co
rner and you had to dodge them and get into this corner. Of course there was certain children never took part - they weren't either strong enough or - they - just weren't inclined that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You never saw teachers make favourites of certain children an
d leave other children out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh yes, they made a favourite of me. Oh I was a favourite, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Because I was very good at school. I was the blue-eyed boy. Now the - although I say this myself - Mr Whittle who was the headmaster of the
 - St Johns school in my day, the primary school - said that I was one out of a hundred as a boy. Well you can imagine, I went at four by the time I wasn't even nine when I was in standard six. I was never in standard three and I was never in standard fiv
e
. I jumped two - I jumped standard three and I jumped standard five - went straight into standard six and I was in standard six ready to go into standard seven, which was the - school - year for people leaving because they left at fourteen and there were 
boys of twelve and thirteen in my class and I was only nine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What about at the boarding school - were they all similar backgrounds there?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh they were much more wealthy - and better better-off people altogether.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you get groups there and 
were children left out there or children singled out by teachers - what happened there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
I can't ever remember - we - no, we had a very good team spirit because we had a football team and a cricket team and - we had out own friends and we used to figh
t amongst each other as you can imagine and - but you see as a boarding school we used to have to march out in two's - like they do, like a crocodile. We'd actually do that, and we used to go to the - the coastguard station along the front at Cliftonville
 
and march really respectably because this being a Jewish school and a lot of other schools - there was the Cliftonville college - there were a whole number of colleges there, it was the - the thing to be respectable because you were somebody if you went t
o a boarding school. And there were \{ILLEGIBLE\}.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
How did you feel when you had to come back to an ordinary school - did you find a vast deal of difference?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No - I don't think I was sensitive - I don't think I was sensitive to it. Because I was more interested in the school itself rather than the - the surroundings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What type of school was this when you came back again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Came back to the Cheetham Central School.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Was it boys and girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh boys and girls together again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What about the teachers here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh I got on very well with one teacher. The headmaster at that time was a man called Race - William Race. He had a nephew also - Billy Race and - there was a man called Derbyshire who was the - chemistry master, I was a fav
ourite of the teachers, and Miss Young. I was Miss Young's real favourite. She coached me perhaps more than the others for the Grammar school. She was a graduate you see -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I don't need to ask whether you liked them or not.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh they liked me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you like school as a whole?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
But let me tell you something about school. That school, I think I may have mentioned it though you may not have recorded it, that school had a - a system of honours. They had a roll of honour. And this roll of honour
, you achieved it by getting good marks for three successive months. If you got really }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 good marks}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  they gave you a little piece of ribbon, it was a red and green ribbon which you tied in your lapel - you sewed it in your lapel. The second month you'd get a 
second one. And the third month you'd get a third one. If you had three of these ribbons and you maintained these three ribbons, I'm not quite sure how long for, you were then - had your name put on the roll of honour and - you got a silver pin - it's a l
ittle - you had to pay sixpence for this pin and it was a tie-pin and the girls had a - a sort of a hat pin and - oh you were very proud if you had one of these things, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You always had one I presume?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I had one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 It was a boys and girls school then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
It was a boys and girls school, yes. And - they also put your name on the roll of honour, you had - I asked this lady next door who was a mistress at that school if they still had these certificates and they were - you know - framed on the
 walls of the school of all the past members of the roll of honour. I have an uncle whose - he recently died at the age of eighty who also had a roll of honour at that school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What was the punishment like here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I never - don't think I ever got punished there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did they use a system of punishment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh they had punishment, yes, you had to go to Mr Race.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Do you remember what it was for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh - sometimes insolence. I'll tell you where the insolence occurred. It didn't occur normally
 in the ordinary classroom but when the class was dispersed at the manual - woodworking class - where they were cheeky and all the rest of it, you know, youngsters messing about with tools and that. It happened then, it happened in the chemical laboratory
 
as well. They used to - they used to mess about because they could hide behind the benches you see. And - the discipline wasn't half as good there but I can remember on one occasion - we were told strictly not to use the planes for sharpening our rulers t
o
 keep the edge clean. And what boys used to do - used to get a plane and they used to get - push it in - I did this - and slice a lump off and I got punished for that - for slicing a lump off. I had a lot of marks taken off me and I think I had lines to d
o and a whole heap of things. I -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You told me about going on to Manchester Grammar and getting a suit there?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 This was after your father died and your circumstances had been much reduced?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes, there were - there were two t
hings about a suit. I had to borrow a relations suit in order to sit for the examination because me clothes were so bad and at one period during the school year I went there for three years, from 1912 to 1915, and I'm not quite sure which - I think it was
 in 1915 I was called to the high master's office, Mr J L Payne - you've heard of J.L. SPayne? Well J.L. Payne is a name to be conjured with - one of the leading in - educationalists of the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Manchester{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} area for the first twenty years of the century, or round about - before Douglas Miller came. J.L. Payne was a very well known man throughout this area, he lived in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Waterpark Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} by the way, he was a friend of Bishop Welden's, he was a friend of the Jewish boys, he was a bachelor.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 He wasn't Jewish though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No. No. He was a - a fellow of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}
St Johns{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}College{\*\xmlclose}, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Oxford{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. A very well - liked person. An extremely fine man in every way. He went - eventually and became the Director of Education for {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}Newfoundland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Yes, he left {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}England{\*\xmlclose} and was a very big man in education in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}Newfoundland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. And I think he must have gone round just before 1920 I think. But he was a high master. He called me to his office and he said that there was a fund which provided for - boys in reduced circumstances - certain things, and if I would go
 to my uncle who was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 tailor}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 and have a suit made he would meet the bill, he would get somebody who would meet the bill. Now whether he did it out of his own pocket or whether he used some fund I never really knew but I got a new suit out of that. My wife's father made it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you enjoy Manchester Grammar?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
I liked it very much but I was very upset for a - two reasons. One of the reasons was I was never able to have the school dinners.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Couldn't afford it. They cost six - they cost sixpence and I couldn't }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 afford}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 it. I used to take sandwiches. But not only that - I couldn't really afford that, but we had a friend who used to give me threeha'pence a day. I used to go to his house and get this threeha'pence and used to buy - a banana o
r some other kind of fruit and I used to take, you know, buns and I used to go to - her father's workshop and eat them there because it wasn't very far away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You didn't like to eat them at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No, well there was - I don't know whether there 
was any real place for them to eat. But - but - only the best - you see, the well off boys had these school dinners. Were down in the basement - it smelt beautiful but I never had them. I'll tell you something about the school because you'll be interested
 in this. And the other thing was that I wanted to go to the Grammar School camps. They used to hold an annual camp at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Grasmere{\*\xmlclose}. And the boys used to go. And - I wanted very much to go but I }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 could never}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  afford it. It wasn't very much but worse than that - t
he Grammar school headmasters were very very progressive and one year they took a boy - a group of boys and went on the Continent. But more than that, in one of the years I can't remember which, they took a group of boys to the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}United States{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Yes. One of the masters took a group of boys to the United States.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Who paid for it - it would be the wealthy boys who went?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Parents - the wealthy people. There were - there were some families - let me tell you something of the families. There was some very wealthy Jewish families, there were the Nahum's who }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 were}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 big shippers. You've heard of Nahum's? Do - do you know - do you know Park Hill on - Bury old Road - Buty {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}New Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 there which is now the Nunnery? That was their house. Park Hill, that's where the Hahums lived. They were the aristocracy of the Jewish families. Oh there were whole score of them. There's Eves and the Marks from Marks and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 Spencer\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  were there at the time you know. - Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Their boys went to school with you did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No, they
 were older than me. Older than me. The people that went to school with me, one of them were very famous, Louis Golding, the writer of Magnolia Street, he was one of the senior boys of my day and there's Alderman Willie Chadwick who was a Mayor of Manches
ter who lives - he's a doctor now - Willie Chadwick was there, he was one of my - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 contemporise}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  but a bit older than me. Then there's Teuben Kelcohen who is a - one of the principle secretaries to the Sunday - one of the big }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 ministries}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, well he must - he's older than me too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 So you really got mostly wealthy boys at Manchester Grammar did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No, no. No, no, no. There were - some very wealthy families because all the leading {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Manchester{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} families, most of them had sons. There was one firm o
f Brunnets, shippers. There were the Behrens family, Frankemburgs. You know the Gewngave Mill rubber company - their - their boys. Well one - one of the boys, Cyril Frankemburg - was captain of the school. But they - some of them have moved away from the 
Jewish community. He was the captain of the school - he got killed in the war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
How did you feel about the difference of wealth between you - did you feel it badly as a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I didn't feel so badly, I'll tell you why. Because I was a member of the 
Jewish Lads Brigade. And - there was a sort of a - a - how shall I put it - a - it was - not a custom - the wealthier Jewish people felt it their duty to look after the poorer children. And - some of the - sons of the wealthy Jewish people were at school 
w
ith me. You know the Mayor - the former Mayor of Salford, Alderman Finburg? Well his son Mark Finburg was at school with me. And I knew - knew him quite well you see and - later on he lived not very far from here and I used to be on speaking terms with hi
m, then there was the - the firm of Ken - Kendall }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4589562 &}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 Jacobs, Norman Jacobs who became a very prominent member of the Jewish community in Manchester. He was at school - with me and there's another boy who was - he's no Sir Alec Oppenheimer, he was the Chancel
lor of Singapore University. I think I mentioned him - I used to go to school with him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 And they used to help you did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No, they didn't help, no, I'm just telling you about the wealthier - and those were in better circumstances. And - that -
 the - the help came when they were members of both - you see, the Grove House Lads Club and the Jewish Lads Brigade were - a combination. One was the social side and the other was the Jewish Lads Brigade side. And the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 The social side of what - the synagogue or the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No, nothing to do with the synagogue or the school. It was just - the Jewish youth movement if you like to put it so. And - there was a Church Lads Brigade and a Boys Life Brigade, and we had the equivalent of it, the Jewish 
Lads Brigade and it was - a kind of a youth club where they had - a place where the boys could come - play ping-pong, play billiards - and they combined that with physical drill and Jewish Lads Brigade and camping. And if you remember I said that I loved 
to go camping and the only holidays that I had from 1912 to about 1923 was by going to camp each year. I went with the Boys Brigade to camp. In fact I was in camp in - just before the war broke out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you benefit from your education - obviously you did?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well - I should say I did well. And I was one - I was a bit fortunate because in the library of the Grove House Lads Club, remember I - I said I was a member of the Jewish Lads Brigade and the Grove House Lads Club, we had one of the officers, a
nd he's got a very famous name because he was Judge Neville Laski, he was a son of - Nathan Laski and the father of Marganita Laski. Well he was an officer and he used to have intellectual pursuits and when the boys were playing billiards or larking about
 
or boxing, whatever they were doing, he used to get a group of youths in the library and have a sort of a quiz. The result of this quiz you got bars of chocolate. And I used to win a lot of bars of chocolate. And Neville Laski was - quite a - I got on ver
y well with him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What age did you eventually leave school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
I left school at fifteen. I matriculated - I was very young mind you - I matriculated in July 1915 - I've got the certificate upstairs and left the Grammar school after that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Would you have stayed on longer if you could have done?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well - J.L. Payne - I was in the - what they call the transitus which was the - in between the fifth form and the sixth form. Biys who were in the upper transitus as I were - was - usually - were being
 trained to go into the sixth preliminary to going in for the university scholarships you see. Well - on my final report by J.L. Payne he used the words - my wife was only reminding me the other day - he called me a rough diamond. And - he knew very well 
that it was pretty hopeless for me - even if I managed to win a scholarship I couldn't maintain myself at all at the school so he said that it - there wouldn't be much purpose in going on into the sixth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Would you have liked to have gone on though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
I don't think so - I wasn't all that keen, because I didn't do too well later on. What happened in the Grammar school, I think the - the curriculum was too hard for me 'cos I was pushed too far. Being so good - and I was rather in the very last bracket 
of those who were allowed to go in for the foundation scholarship - I was a foundation scholar by the way, there were only about forty given in the whole of the area.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What was a foundation scholar?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 A foundation scholar was a person who went to t
he Manchester Grammar school as a scholar as a result of an examination called the foundation scholarship. Which; gave you the right to be - a member of the Grammar school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Who ran the foundation scholarship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 It was run by the - by the Governers
. Yes, yes, oh yes. It was the - it was the premier - it was the premier award in the Lancashire area - used to come from all over Lancashire, boys came from Blackpool and Bolton and Wigan and all over the show to sit for that exam and they had only - I t
h
ink - there were less than forty a year and it was, as I say, the prize of the year. And - I can remember that my name was in the Guardian 'cos they published the names of all they boys who got foundations in the Guardian and it's still a great honour. My
 son also is a foundation scholar and it's something which you can - you know - well you can }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 mention}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 , I was a foundation scholar. My particular scholarship - Lord James who was the high master at the time said that an open scholarship trinity was one of the
 greatest prizes of the academic world.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 And your son got it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 He got it, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you do any evening classes after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Yes. Now after I left school I was - going on to tell you that - J.L. Payne, knowing that I was a shade
 better than some of the other boys who left in the fifth - if you were in 5C you usually left and either went in your father's business or went into something. He said what did I want to do? And I said I wanted to be a chemist - an organic chemist. Well 
t
here weren't any facilities in those days. There was - oh the runner of the - the forerunners of I.C.I. but there was Blakeley, the Brenner - Bennermons or whoever it was at Blakeley and Leichtenstein - some name or other, I just can't remember the names 
- and he didn't think that was such a good idea. So as a second choice I said I'd go into pharmaceutical chemist and he then sent me to - a chemist in - Mosston - Lightbowne Road Mosston and I was sent as a - you know - probationer - person - and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 This was your first full time job was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
This was my first job - sent by the - by the Grammar school. Then I went to this chemist I was turned down and - because the chemist happened to be Jewish and didn't want any Jewish boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Why didn't he want Jewish boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Now don't ask me. He - was - against having Jewish boys. I came home and I was in tears and I went back to the school and told Mr Payne and he said, oh, we'll fix you up. And I was then sent to a friend of his - a man who was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 very}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  bi
g man in the former British Westinghouse - Sir - Sir Arthur Fleming he became - he was the head of the education department and the research department and I was then apprenticed to Metro - well it wasn't Metro Vickers - it was the British Westinghouse.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Can you tell me how much pay you got in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh - I can remember to a penny. I got six shillings - six shillings a week, yes. Because I was fifteen. I would only have got five if I was fourteen but I got six shillings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How many years apprenticeship did you have to serve?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh I've got my certificate upstairs. I served a normal - normal trade apprenticeship which was a - an indentured apprenticeship which I received the certificate, 'til I was twenty-one. I had it upstairs, the certificate, it's -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 And you had six shillings all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh no, no, no. No, no, no. It wasn't - an indentured - apprenticeship which was covered by a large fee, it was over a sixpenny stamp, it was in the nature of a gentleman's agreement, you cou
ld break it without any indemnity you see, but I didn't break it of course and - there they had an apprentice school as well you know. Because -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You were training then to become what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 To be trained to become an engineer I suppose but they didn't
 - they didn't - they didn't actually train people to be engineers. See, when I say they didn't train them they wouldn't take you on as an apprentice engineer. I was taken on as an apprentice electrical fitter. If you became an engineer it would be due to
 
your own efforts afterwards, but they would never take anybody on as an indentured engineer until later - they did later but I was what they called a trade apprentice. I hadn't - I couldn't bring anything in the way of technical qualifications - I was onl
y a boy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 When you were an apprentice did you work Saturdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you have a half day Saturday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well let me tell you what happened as an apprentice. I started on September he twentieth 1915 as an apprentice and in those days t
he hours of work in the works - not in the offices - the works at Trafford Park, the British Westinghouse as it was in those days, of fifty-two and a half hours a week. From seven o'clock in the morning until half past five with an hour for lunch and seve
n 'til twelve on a Saturday. Fifty-two and a half hours. And that - was for the same for apprentices - the same for -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you have holidays with pay in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No, no, no. No, no. No - in fact you - if you came a quarter of an hour late you had it stopped out of your pay.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you feel it was a fair wage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 A fair wage - at six bob?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How did you go on with it - did you give any of it to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh I - I can - I can tell - I had to give it all to her except the fare. I t
hink I - I used to - used to do a little bit outside, remember I told you I went and - did little jobs like this Sunday morning -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 This wasn't while you were at school - this was when you'd started work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh this - when I started work. I also did 
other little bits, you know, to earn a copper or so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Collecting on Sunday morning and helping on the market?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Collection on Sunday - helping on the market and going to the workshop and doing things there as well you see for the - tailor shop and any other way which I could make one penny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 This was to help your mother out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you ever keep any of the money for yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No, I - I must have had spending money but as fifteen or - a boy of fourteen or fifteen - I di
dn't need a lot because I used to go almost every night to this - Grove House Lads Club where - for a penny o week or tuppence a week I think we paid, we had a - a youth club so I didn't need much - didn't need any, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How did you get on with the people you worked with at the Westinghouse?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh I must tell you this 'cos this was the biggest scream going. I don't know whether I told you this story but I'll tell - I'll tell you because it'll be significant. One year, I can't remember which year it w
as but the - date on which the Jewish Lads Brigade went to camp didn't coincide with the works holiday at Trafford Park and consequently if I was going to have a wee - ten days off that was the - week and subsequently the weekend which - came to the old B
a
nk Holiday Monday. It was the ten days prior to that. That was the - the holiday. But the Grove House Lads Club boys used to go to camp the Friday before that Bank Holiday and had Bank Holiday week so I would then be faced with having no wages for two wee
ks which I couldn't stand you see. Too much - to have no wages. So - there were one or two apprentices who were - evidently fixed the same way, and one of them was rather a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 These would be Jewish apprentices?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No, no, no, no. I think there was on
ly one other Jewish boy who was an apprentice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you find any prejudice here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Not at all. No, none at all. This boy, he became quite a big man in Westinghouse later on, he was a really sharp - sharp one. He says, do you know there's a scheme w
hereby people who don't want to take their holidays during the works week - what was called the works holiday week, they can work in the maintenance department whilst the works is closed down and earn some money and - so I then went to see a man called Er
n
ie Heath I think his name was and he was the foreman and I said I would like to work during works week in the maintenance department. And - he asked me which department I was in. I told him and he said all right, he said, you will go with another boy and 
y
our job will to clean the motors you know, in the big machine shops they used to have motors which were up in the air and they used to operate shafting from which all the belts came down to operate the machine and we used to have to climb up and take all 
t
he dust and all the muck out of these motors and they gave it boys to do you see and the other things was to - repair and - either renew the brushes, the carbon brushes and we had a right old time. I enjoyed it very much, yes I liked climbing up in the ai
r
 and messing about. And - but the joke - that's not so much - the joke of this was that this boy - put me up to a trick. He said, when they ask you what your rate is don't tell them that you only get six bob a week, you tell them your rate is ten bob a we
e
k, you see, and then when you get your pay they'll pay you at the rate of ten bob a week. Which I did. I said - when they asked me what me rate was I said ten shillings. So when it came to getting my week's pay I got ten shillings instead of six shillings
 
and I thought this was wonderful. See. Marvellous. And I went to camp and felt like - well I had another four shillings you see, the equivalent of. When I came back and I received my pay the next week we had to stand in line on a Friday night you know - a
n
d the foreman would call your name out, he'd give him your clock card, he'd stamp it and give you a pay packet. I got my pay packet, I think there was only about sixpence in it. They'd found out that I'd told - and they actually took the four shillings of
f me and I was left with sixpence I think that week.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How did you feel about the work and how did you feel about the employers?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well I - I had a very good time. You see - coming as I did from the Grammar school they had high hopes of me so I was 
put in a research department. And - I was telling my wife the other day, we had a whale of a time because it wasn't like work at all. The first day was a bad day - there was what they called mica-}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 insulation}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  which they used on electric motors and part of th
e job of the research department was to weigh this out, for some purpose or other, and you - I spent the first day with a chemical balance weighing slabs of mica - small slabs of mica, and when I came home I said to mother, I'm not going back. I hated it.
 
I said, I didn't want to go to - British Westinghouse to weigh on a chemical balance and it was - I didn't use the word bring but - lousy or something like that, I didn't want to go. But she prevailed on me to go back and I did. And I suppose I must be th
a
nkful I did because the alternative was to go into one of these waterproof workshops or something like that which was very bad. Very unhealthy. Anyway I went back and into the same department and things were - were - turned out better because there was an
other boy who - I was friendly with for the next forty-odd years -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You stayed there forty-odd years did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No. Because I - I knew him - not forty-odd years - that's a bit of an untruth but to getting on that way. I knew him in 1915, he went into the Army in 1917, I came back into a department that he was a member of in 1925 I stayed 'til 1948 -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 This was at British Westinghouse?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well it became the British Westinghouse, Metro Vicker and then finally A.E.I. and when I used to go back - after I left them in 1948 until about 1950 odd I used to go back and go and see Stanley Kirkland.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 So you were there from leaving school until 1948?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No, no. No, not all the time. I left in 1923 and went to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Rugby{\*\xmlclose}. And then stayed there just over a year. A year and a half.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What did you do at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Rugby{\*\xmlclose}?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
But I'm going on a bit too fast aren't I. Let me finish with these apprentices. As I say, when I was fifteen I became a trade apprentice and - to show you that there was no discrimination I was 
a member of the apprentices football team. The war was on as you can imagine, the only sort of activity outside was sort of picnics. We used to go to a place called Windybottom Farm and the apprentices used to go there and have sports. You couldn't do ver
y
 much beyond going to a park or - somewhere near, and they had these activities for apprentices and I used to take part in them and as I played football, I was a member of the apprentices football team. We used to go swimming. And - as I say, I was treate
d
 like anybody else was no discrimination whatever. Then - something important - something rather important turned up. They picked out a number of apprentices - oh incidentally I ought to tell you that whilst you were being trained as an apprentice you wer
e
 allowed to go so many periods a week to the apprentice school - they had an apprentice school where you did a little bit of mechanical drawing and other technical work in connection with the work that you were doing you see. And - I was a member of this 
school as I told you I was pretty bright lad. I was picked out for a scholarship. This scholarship enabled me to go to the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 Manchester}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  College of Technology every Monday, it was called the Monday day course, and - as a soft of a slight sideline or a comical 
sideline - they used to put on my drawing board when I happened to be in the drawing office later on, Harry Cahm, D.C.M. You know what the D.C.M. stood for. Doesn't come Mondays.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you like your work or would you have preferred to do another type o
f work do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well I liked the work very much - as a boy. I went - you see, there wasn't any real training scheme as such, in other words, it was quite haphazard. You stayed so many months in one department and then they either moved you to an
other department or you asked to be moved and after I'd been in this - research department where we had a whale of a time really because some of the experiments were most spectacular. We used to do experiments - one of them was really a }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 marvellous}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  one. Use
d to have great big brass spheres and we used to cause sparks to travel across them - what they call a spark gap and - this was a precursor to many very high voltage experiments which - I didn't understand what was going on but one of the things - perhaps
 
one of the amusing incidents will be better. We were allowed - we were allowed to go - out - well we were told to go and put samples of transformer oil out in the open to see if it collected moisture because one of the tests we used to do was to test batc
h
es of transformer oil and they used to test these between very much smaller gaps. We used to have a - what they call a testing transformer that got a very very high voltage and caused the electricity to flash over and break the oil down. Well that was par
t
 of our test. But before we did that we were allowed to put samples of this oil in beakers, in sort of open beakers, in the yard of the works. Well the only place we could found was some huge disused drains and we used to go with these samples and get los
t for half a day there - we used to sleep in the - drains - Stanley Kirkland and I used to go. And he used to say, where the devil have you been? We'd say, oh we've been, you know, chasing these samples and whatnot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 So you weren't afraid of your boss obviously?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well the boss wasn't really a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 boss}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 , he was only a - over apprentice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you have a trade union or professional body in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Later on but not - not until 19 - not until 1919.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you feel there was a division of inter
est between workers and employers in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No, we - we - we had - I wasn't conscious of trade unionism until 1919.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Do you think there was a big difference between the craftsman and the ordinary worker?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well let me tell you something 
about that and here again the value of my education was really priceless. You see, after leaving this research department which I - really didn't - know what was going on really you know 'cos - there was nobody really - use the word really so many times -
 
there wasn't anybody directing my - training at all, it was purely haphazard, had to do, you know, do the best you could But I decided I want to go into a machine shop - get more practice. So they put me into a machine shop. But I wasn't put in the machin
e
 shop proper, I was put on what they call the marking off bench which was a - quite a high grade of job where they had a huge flat steel base about - oh much bigger than this and about six inches think where the jobs used to be marked out for machining. B
u
t the point I'm making is that the men on the marking off bench realized that I was a bit of a mathematician and in return for me teaching them trigonometry and things of that kind they taught me some really first class fitting and I learnt a lot of pract
i
cal work, I became very - adept at really good fitting. In fact I made what they call a scriber - a marking off tool - I was allowed to use the machines - I went on machine later on but I was - trained by these chaps to work with machines and I made a mac
h
ine for marking off which was an adjustable one which was a very fine piece of work, although I say it myself, and I was helped by all the craftsmen because I used to do little jobs for them, you know, show them hose to - dissect circles or bisect circles
 and do other little things which were very helpful for their job you see, and teach them the rudiments of trigonometry and what not. So - I got this in return and - I think I was a very fair fitter in my way.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 But did you notice a difference between crafts men and other workers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well I was going on to say, these - these chaps who had this slightly higher grade were better class people. Oh yes, they were better, they weren't - the others - some of them were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 semi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 -skilled. The - the top men were the
 turners. A man on what they call a centre lathe was a top craftsman, but a man on a drilling machine - was - he was a - ch - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 semi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  - well he could be semi-literate. All that - all that he had to do was to use this machine with a drill - we used to mark off
 where the holes were, we used to mark them in such a way that all he had to do was to bring a lever down and get the point of the drill in a certain - what we call a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 centre pockmark}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  and pull it through and drill it. So they were literally - well they were
n't unskilled, they weren't labourers but they weren't like the - the turners.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What do you think was the other difference socially between them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 They were much better paid as well. Oh yes, were better class altogether.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Do you ever remember 
anyone helping your mother look after the home or family? After your father died when you became in reduced circumstances?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Yes. The only - I don't know whether I mentioned earlier, in order to help out - just as - almost - a few weeks after my father
 died they held a dance, try and raise funds, I think I mentioned that didn't I. After that the only thing we got was help from the Board of Guardians.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How did they treat you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh well you would go - me mother used to go and stand in a queue and 
receive some - charity.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How did she feel about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 She didn't like it at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You don't remember her mentioning how they treated her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No, they didn't treat you badly but nobody wanted to be seen - at these places and as I say, me mother then went to work if you - I mentioned - she went into a cap works. To - as a cap worker.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
In the Jewish community would they come in and help if your mother was ill or confined to bed - was there a great deal of neighbourliness amongst the Jewish community?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
I really can't - I'm not really conscious of that - it - as a boy, you know, you wouldn't notice it a great deal, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What about relatives - would they help you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I'll tell you what used to happen when - when mother was having a b
aby we got thrown out of the house sort of thing, we were told to get out of the way sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
When they were preparing it - a lot of them - children were born at home and the kitchen would be arranged with all hot water and things like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You mean you children were sent out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 We were turned out. And went to me grandmother or somewhere you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Who looked after your mother when she had children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Me grandmother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 She didn't have a doctor or a midwife or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh they'd have a midwife, yes, and a doctor of course. Oh yes, yes, there -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Would you not have relatives come in and help then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Not a lot. No, no, no. They all had their own - children to look after you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did your parents have relatives living nearby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 We had friends - great friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 But no relatives living nearby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
I must tell you - talk about friends. You know there's a tradition amongst Jewish people that during the Passover when they celebrate what they call 
the Sadanite which is similar to the last supper of the apostle and that - there's one period where you - open the door and any passing stranger who might be within earshot, you more or less say that if you're in need of hospitality just come in and - and
 somebody actually came into our house once and stayed for - became a lodger. This was when we lived in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Therlmere Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. This was when I was about seven or eight I should imagine. Yes, there was a man - there was a man called Leon, he was a member of a - a
 family who came from Spain he said and he said, he was an ascendant of a famous General De Leon - we didn't believe him. But - he was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 He came in for a meal and then stayed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 He had to be in the area and he came to this - this period during thi
s ceremony and stayed and never went away. Like the man who came to dinner. He was in - he was in our house for about - couple of years I think. He payed - he didn't pay very much. He was an old man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 And your mother was soft hearted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 And me moth
er kept him on as a - as a lodger. But we had - me mother had some friends - oh I must tell you about this. She had one friend - a woman called Rosie. She was - because she had - her name was Rosie but she had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 Rosie}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  cheeks and she was a comic woman - she u
sed to make my mother laugh and there's one story about this which I - me mother's name by the way was Fanny and she happened -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 That was her English name was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No, Fanny - Fanny English - Fanny Cahm, and - she was out with this Rosie and this Rosie was incidentally }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7426541 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 to a - second time, she - I think her first husband either divorced her or something - to a very much older man and she didn't like this old man and she used to go out with me mother. This old man used to visit us. But this p
articular incident I want - incident I want to relate to you. They happened to be in town - oh I'm not quite sure when it would be - it would be before the end of the war I think. Oh it'd be before 1918. And they were walking along 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Cannon Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, somewhere near the Cathedral I think they were perhaps further down, only at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Corporation Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and me mother saw on the ground a wallet absolutely chock full of money. And - me mother picked this up and this Rosie said to me mother, she said, Fanny, look gelt, ge
lt is the Yiddish - it's the Yiddish name for money - gelt. She'd never seen so much money in her life and they were holding this money like that in their hands when a woman came up to them and shouted out, she said, you saw me drop that. And she snatched
 out of their hands and ran off with it. I'm not quite sure how much was it - it was a satchel full of money. It was - I don't know how many notes, I think it was gold and all sorts.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 And your mother was very poor at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh they were both very poor. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Your mother came suddenly from good circumstances to reduced circumstances as?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh she was able, as I say, to employ a maid at one time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did the maid live in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Do you remember the maid at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh yes,
 I - I think I told you a story about one maid didn't I. And you know I was reminded of that by something that was said on the - was it the programme - one of the radio programmes I think - was going to tell you was that reminded me of the story that we h
a
d a maid and this maid left and I started crying and I said I wanted this maid back, I think her name was Mary, and me mother wanted to know why I wanted this maid back. 'Cos we got another maid and I didn't like this maid you see. What do you want Mary b
ack for? I said, because when Mary washed us we were clean for three days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did the maids have their own room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh they had - they had their own room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did they eat with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes they would eat with us, yes. They would look after the chil
dren, they would dress the children, they would take them out in the prams. Oh yes, they had maids.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How would you address them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh by their name. Yes, Mary - one was called Kate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How would they address your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Mrs of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did they have anything to do with the discipline of you children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
One older woman did but the others - they were only young girls. And we used to lark with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 And they more or less looked after you children
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well they were only about fi
fteen or sixteen I imagine. They were only youngsters. There were a lot of them from the country. Staffordshire or from - you know - mid Lancashire or some from Ireland.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 But they had food with you - they had kosher food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh they had - they ate j
ust the same as everybody else, yes. But I'll tell you what did happen, it didn't happen in our family but it happened in other families. The parents would have butter but the children would only have margarine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Perhaps because of cost. We 
know one family particularly, it never happened in our family we would have butter - mother could afford it of course and I used to go to the Maypole, you know -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Was this before or after your father died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh this was after. Before 1918. Do you k
now the - Great Cheetham Street? You know before you come to where Leicester Road Starts, just in that row of shops there was the Maypole and I used to go for a pound of best butter - cost a shilling in those days. And used to get it off this big slab and
 
get these two pats. And margarine in those days was really poor. It was like axle grease. Very bad - about threepence or fourpence a pound but - we didn't have margarine most of the time, occasionally when we just were in bad circumstances but most times 
we had butter. But this, as I say, in some families the children were only given margarine and the parents had butter.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did your parents have a lot of friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh we had a lot of friends, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Were they your father's or father's and mother's friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No, I don't much about my father's friends you see because I say he died too early. But mother's friends I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did they come into your home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh yes. Especially - one of our festivals is called the festival of the harvest. Coincides
 with the harvest festival - it's called Feast of Tabernacles and they build - sort of a temporary tabernacle in the gardens or in the back yards as they were. We had a friend who lived in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Marlborough Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} opposite where the Co-op was, Did you ever know where the Co-op was in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Marlborough Road
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. It's all gone now isn't it? Well they used to build one of these - su}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 hers they're called. And the sucher was built about September and the feature about it was that you had to be able to see the stars through the top
 - it didn't have a proper roof. And it was built of orange boxes and timer and really ramshackle. I used to help to paste it with wallpaper and what not, but the great part about that was that at the end - oh by the way, and they used to hang fruit from 
the roof, apples and pears and grapes and our greatest joy was to go on the last day which is called Sil hattarra which is the rejoicing of the law when they pull all the fruit down and the kids get all the - marvellous.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did they visit friends a lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well we used to visit these people particularly - we were always visiting friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Would you go for meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No, we wouldn't go really for meals, no, you might have a cup of tea or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Were friends allowed to call casually at your house or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh they were always coming in and out, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Neighbours tool?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Not so much neighbours but friends. Neighbours did. But they didn't run in and out very much but there were families that were always running in and out and they had a name for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
I mean they - they were known - well known as - their house was always - with somebody carrying on in - you know - running in and out and - making a sort of free house of it as it were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 They s
ay in those days when you were young that people made their own amusements - what did your parents do when they got together with friends, did they make music or play games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh father - some of them played cards. The men - played a lot of cards. Yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What did the women do and the children?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Women used to gossip.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 And what about the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
The children - oh we played with - we had different toys, we had diables and tops and things like that. Indoors. Well my wife was only tellin
g me the other day her brothers, and I had one, we had what they call magic lanterns. And we used to buy these little strips of coloured slides - they were about that long all coloured and we used to go up in a bedroom and put a sheet over on the wall and
 
we had these little magic lanterns - I think they had a candle inside or a little oil lamp and - and we used to throw this image on the wall and we used to charge either a farthing or a ha'penny for the kids to come and watch. That was one of the things. 
A
nother thing we used to - as children, we used to have these - especially in winter. Used to get a cocoa tin and fill it with cinders and - cotton wool and all sorts and have a miniature brazier to keep our - keep us warm. We played at that. We used to pl
a
y at, I don't know whether you know the - the game of - throwing bricks at a - at - used to build a little sort of mound of bricks - well we - straight like a - like one of those but of course the bricks were irregular and put the can on the top and - use
d to stand away and throw bricks - bricks or stones to knock the can off. But the game which we played outside was piggy - tip-cat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you play it in the street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No, we played it opposite where we lived. We lived opposite a rec. or a - in St Jam
e's Road there's a big old ground that played football and other recreation grounds and I was very good at it because I was a good jumper. You know - do you know tip-cat, do you know piggy? You know the game? And we played at piggy - the - in some parts o
f
 Lancashire they play with one end sharpened - we had two ends sharpened and we used to pinch people's brooms you know because a broom made a marvelous - made a marvelous piggy you see, it was a piece of rounded wood about that big and - it would be about
 
that long with two sharp ends and we'd get a - a stick like that size - broom handle, and what you do is you hit it and when it's up in the air you hit it and you've got to hit it so far so that the - it's more than seven strides, no less than seven we us
ed to say you see and I was very good at that. And - that was one of the games. But this - throwing - a tin can, we used to throw on the way home from school you know. We used to love it, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What was black rabbit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well in Therlmere Street where
 we lived - the houses were much closer than this and the - the doors had knockers, swing knockers and you'd tie a piece of black cotton from the knocker of that one to the knocker of this, then knock - there was one old woman that we always baiting. And 
we used to knock on her door, she would come to the door - open the door of course knock the other one. They would come out. Have you never heard of black rabbit? It was called black rabbit and we used to play that game in - Therelmere Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Were you
 ever taken out visiting neighbours, friends or relatives? And who did you go with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh went with me mother. Yes, when we were younger we went - quite a lot. We had one or two friends who weren't members of the family and we visited them of course. Bu
t the - the main visiting would be to the family - especially me grandmother. Me grandmother's house was a sort of centre where all the family sort of congregated, we'd get quite crowds and some of our happiest moments were going - they lived in Cheetham 
f
or a time. That was when me grandfather was alive too. And we'd stay quite late and - we used to love coming back at mid - almost at midnight especially in the summertime when the - you know - nice moonlight nights and it was a walk of about twenty minute
s to half hour from where me grandmother lived to home and that was the nicest part of the day, coming back in the middle of the night, especially when we were younger.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Were you taken shopping and who did you go with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well if I went out shopping at all it was with me mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you never go at all with your father?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
The only time I went out with him was very very occasionally to the pantomime or something of that order. Went out with me mother - to a local - the local shop but if it - 
if I can remind you, we had a grocery shop and consequently we didn't do a lot of grocery shopping 'cos we had shops you see, we were - we had a number of shops and so that we didn't do a great deal of - you know, food shopping at all. Now with clothing -
 
I suppose - we went - went to Lewis's or - quite often went to Lewis's, Pauldens we used to go to. And - but we were all boys so there wasn't a great deal of - that time - you see, with girls they - I think they do more buying of clothes don't they for gi
r
ls. Well when I was nine and I was there for two years so that in - perhaps the formative years between nine and eleven - you might be at home doing the sort of shopping we were at a school and consequently we didn't do any shopping at all. And perhaps up
 to the age of nine - seven, you didn't do much you were out playing most of the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you go out with just your father - did your father take you out alone?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Not a lot no, no, because he was away a lot too, see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you do anything special on Bank Holidays - I know you went to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Blackpool{\*\xmlclose} for a holiday you told me?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh yes, we went to Blackpool.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you go regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I think we went each year, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Do you remember what you did when you got there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Played on th
e sands. I don't - collecting shells and played on the sands. We did very - very little else. We'd go on the big dip - we'd go on the big wheel, I remember going on the wheel - I never remember going on - in the tower until much later. Never went up the t
ower until I was quite grown up. But I do remember going on the wheel. In fact, I think - I think I'd been on the wheel at New Brighton too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you go anywhere special for Bank Holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes. We used to go to Daisy Nook. Do you know Daisy Nook? 
Yes. And do you know, that many years afterwards I took my son. Went on bikes to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 And your wife?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No, to Daisy Nook to show him where we used to go because he did - we went to Daisy Nook and went to Bo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13378146\charrsid1644444 g}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 gart Hole Clough and I took Eric to show hi
m - 'course it was very different in later years, but Boggart Hole Clough we used to go to Arms Hill. Do you know Arms Hill? Well - Arms Hill was a place where - and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Heaton
{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} of course. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Heaton{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, Arms Hill, Boggart Hill Clough and Daisy Nook were all
 places that we went. On Bank Holidays. I'll tell you what we did do which was rather interesting, it was in 1911 which is about the time you're speaking of isn't it. I went from Strangeways to Salford Docks to stand in a queue to go into - to visit the c
ruiser H.M.S. Bristol that came to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Manchester{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 and that was a day. There were I was only about - I was about eleven, that's all. And we walked all the way through {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Trafford Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Cross Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and stood in this queue and we went through a cruiser and two dest
royers which was a wonderful event - it never happened to me before. That was in 1911. And the other time I went to that area when there was a huge fire at the docks and we went all the way from Strangeways to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
