\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did your father go out a great deal or did he stay at a home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well - no, he went out a lot. I think he wa
s a member of a Jewish working mens club which was the main Jewish club of the day. A very famous club and still is - the Jewish working mens club.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did he take part in sports or go to a pub or anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I don't think he went to a pub b
ut if you remember that he - he mixed with a lot of business people and he used to go to different towns, he went to London and he went to Nottingham and he went to Liverpool, and one or two other places, to do these commissions for land surveying and of 
c
ourse he used to stay at hotels and - was away quite a bit. But the thing - I think I've mentioned this - the thing I remember really most my father and mother went to the Franco-Vritish exhibition in London and I remember them coming back - my father cam
e
 back with his watch which they'd taken the glass off and they'd painted the Tricolour and the Union Jack on the face of it, they did that there, with the date and they put the glass back again. I remember him bringing this watch an - showing me these two
 flags, crossed flags, on the dial of it, that was, I think, 1908.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did he take part in any sport?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No, no. Not at all. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Did they belong to any savings clubs, boot clubs, funeral clubs or sick clubs or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well - oh -
 no, not all but a lot of Jewish people belonged to a burial society, in fact I still do. I still do. It was at one time tuppence per week. And you paid this tuppence per week for the privilege of being buried in a Jewish cemetery when you died and a prov
ision of perhaps one or two coaches and a minister to - you know - give the last - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 well}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  the last rites is all right because that's perfect -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Do you remember your father's funeral and who went
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh yes, I remember that very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 And the type of dress they wore?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
You don't wear anything special - we don't wear mourning at all. But you have this renting of the garment over the coffin which was done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 It was done over the coffin when your father died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes, they do it over the coffin
, yes, and they do it to the closest blood relations of the deceased.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What happened to you boys when your father died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well when me father died I was eleven and I had brothers who were younger than me and me older brother, one elder brother and 
- we were taken - we weren't - we didn't actually go to the cemetery but when they came back to the house where we lived the have a - what they call a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 Shiva}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  which is seven days mourning when the mourners don't go out of the house at all. They stay in the h
ouse and visitors come in to visit them and prayers are said and - the first night I think we were taken to a relation and the funeral was the next day and after the funeral we went back to the house where we had these prayers you see. And we stayed in th
ere for seven days. It - it isn't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Who went to your father's funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well all me - me mother's brothers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 But not you children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
I think me elder brother went but I didn't go, no. But - he was - you see, he was thirteen so -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Do yo
u remember what happened afterwards - did they al come back home as they do in a Christian house for a meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
They all come back - all come back home, it isn't really a meal. What - what happens when they come back from a funeral, it happens more or l
ess consistently through - for all - I think even orthodox and reform Jews are the same - the close relatives of the family are not supposed to sit on ordinary chairs - they sit on stools. And they're not supposed to prepare the meal themselves. Friends a
nd relations come in and they prepare a meal and it's not a proper meal in the ordinary way. It's a lot of symbolic things. For instance they -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did this happen at your father's funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh it happens, happens even today. Yes, because it - it neve
r fails. It's the same all the way through. They have certain foods like hard boiled eggs and and onions cut up and salt herring. All sort of - bitter things. And - they have these - I don't know if you know what a bagel is. It's like a ring - a bread rin
g. It's a hard boiled one. And they have these buttered and buns buttered and tea or coffee, whatever it is and it's supposed to be a privilege for your neighbours and your other relations to wait on you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 And this happened when your father died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh it happens, yes, just the same, yes. It - it - it - I've never seen any real change anywhere. Even amongst - well I'm not being too many reform members of the reform }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 congregations}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  but they still do very much the same. And the only thing I haven't been t
o is - it goes on - is the - some members of the Jewish community are recremated but I've never been to a cremation. Always been a burial. And there is a - a spot in Blakely reserved for me. And my wife.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How did you get on with your brothers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Hah - I must tell you about this.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Was there any one you felt especially close to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Not really but I was going to tell you quite the opposite. My elder brother had a peculiar habit - when he wanted to eat he used to get in the kitchen and lock all of us out and we couldn't get in,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Why did he do this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
I don't know - don't ask me. He did that and yet - I don't know whether I mentioned to you - I used to sleep in the same bed with my elder brother when we were younger and he had quite a nice 
voice and we used - used to harmonise and the particular song that I can remember was the Chocolate Soldier. We used to do very well with that. 'Cos I was on a choir you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Was there any of your brothers or your mother or father or grandmother that
 you felt particularly close to as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No, not - not - not specially, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Who did you play with as a child - your brothers or sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Didn't play with me brothers. Never had any sisters. No sisters. Not - not at all. Played with neighbours children and - and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Where?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh we played on the rec what they call the rec and we played, I think I remember telling you about this marvelous double entry we had where we used to jump from wall to wall from the backyards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Were you free to play with anyone you wanted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Any one. Anyone you wanted, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You weren't stopped from playing with anyone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What were your hobbies when you were at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 My hobby -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you go fishing or walking, bicycling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Not - not fishing - I liked cycling, I - did I ever tell you about that bike I bought from a rag and bone man for about one and sixpence I think. Oh yes. I was dying for a bicycle, this was when I was about - eleven I should say. That would be round abou
t 1911 - 1912. And one particularly day the rag and bone man came round with his cart and on it was a bicycle. Well is considered - consisted really of nothing more than a frame - handlebars, not a - not a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 proper}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  saddle and two }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 wheels}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  and a bit of a chain,
 no peddles, just the spindles and - I said how much do you want for that? And eventually having got it for about a shilling or something of that kind, and we lived in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}
Howarth Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} which I don't think is there now. It's just - do you know where the Cricketers Arms was, at the bottom of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Coker Road{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}? Well it was at the back of there, there's Mount Pleasant, the hill going up and where the warders houses are now, the prison houses was a flat field where we used to play football. It was a cinder track. The Wat
erloo Roa ground there and we took this bicycle, when I say we of course the other kids all get round, and I tried to learn - in fact I did learnt to ride this bicycle on this like cinder track. And - I was doing very well with this and I got so - sort of
 confident that I left the ground and started going down {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Mount Pleasant{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Well it had no brakes on it and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Mount Pleasant{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} is a - a fairly steep hill. And I wanted to turn into Howarth Street where we lived, and I couldn't turn the wheels had no tyres on so it
 didn't turn round properly and the bike went flat and I sprawled across the pavement and there was a house at the corner of Mount Pleasant and Howarth Street where the window was one of those windows that came almost down to the ground, it was a casement
 window. And the bike and my elbow went right thorough this window and knocked a plant pot off. And - the lady came out and confiscated the bike and I think she sold it for two bob to pay for the damages, I never got it back anymore.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you have any other hobbies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well I haven't finished about - I haven't finished about bikes. Later on my brother and I decided we want - wanted a bike. And we had to means of buying a bike in the ordinary way and we got a man, I wonder if you remember, the corner of 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Broad Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Bury New Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 there was a - corner - sharp corner there where there was a cycle shop called Strauss, a man called Strauss. He also had a shop in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Great Euston Street{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} and he used to build bikes. And we saved a lot of money up and we bought a bike between us. And we went to Pickmere, oh all over - we used to have it in turns. He used it one day or more - more than I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 very}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  got it because he was older than me and on once particular day, this same 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Mount pleasant{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} place, I was coming down {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Mount Pleasant{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} and the same sort of thing happened. This time I went into a wall. And the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You weren't exactly a good cyclist obviously.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Not at that time, I was very good afterward. And the front wheel bumped into this wall and the frame buckled so that
 the two wheels came close together, top bar instead of being straight was buckled like that. And that was the end of that bike. Oh I got into an awful row over that, me brother carried on. Then I had a bike that was left by an uncle who went to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}America{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. He went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}America{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 in 1913 and left a very big old bike which I confiscated.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You were in clover then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Yes, until my cousin who thought he had as much right to it as - pinched the bike off me and eventually later on fitted it up with an auto wheel. Yes. That was later on about 1915 - 1916. He was - he was older.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Tell me about your pocket money as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Were you given any pocket money and how much and what did you spend it on?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Pocket money - when - before I went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}
}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Margate{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}College{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 I used to get I think a penny or threehapence, it depended on the cost of the comic called the Jester. Used to take the Jester. Because there was certain detective or something like that. I think it was a penny and at one time threehapence. 
I think I got a penny or threehapence when I was - up to the age of about nine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 That was good in those days wasn't it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Do you think it was good? Penny. Saturday penny - we talked about the Saturday penny. You could get four ounces of sweets for
 a penny you know. You'd get tiger nuts - tiger nuts. Used to buy the Jester and a ha'porth of tiger nuts, you see, and aniseed balls, used to buy all those things. But when we went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Margate{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} I was really in clover because I got ninepence. That was from 1911. Me elder brother got a shilling. I got ninepence, and me younger brother got sixpence.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 This was when you were in boarding school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 When we - when we were at boarding school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What did you spend it on then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh yes, I remember I told
 you. We had all kinds of - you know - fads and things. One week we all bought water pistols. I think you got a water pistol for about sixpence. We went round squiring water at each other. Then we went mad on kites. Then - I think we're mad on }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 balloons}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  and
 the thing - I always remember more than anything else was there was a shop in the main - shopping centre at Margate and - if I think I remember I told you, the only time that we were allowed free to go to out on our own was after lunch on Friday when we 
h
ad our pocket money and until tea time there was no restriction on where we went with the exception of certain parts of Margate - Funland and all those rough places we weren't supposed to go. But to Cliftonville and round there, and there was one shop tha
t used to sell rock cakes. And I used to buy thirty-one rock cakes for sixpence.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What on earth did you do with thirty-one rock cakes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 That's right, yes. - I don't know how many I ate but we used to }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 smuggle}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  them into the dormitory and we used to e
at them - I think they lasted 'til about Tuesday and these -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 They were rock cakes by then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well they were little, you know, little - little thin cakes - they weren't bad. I think we got through most of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What was the discipline like at your boarding school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh it was very good, yes. It wasn't severe, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Was it a Jewish boarding school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
It was entirely Jewish boarding school, yes. We - oh it was very nice because I think if I remember I told you that - from early summer or perhaps the end of the spring -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You were telling me about boarding school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Boarding school and I was saying that for a larger part of the summer time we were in whites. And were white shorts and white shirts and ties in the school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Was it good food and everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh yes. The only thing that I can remember is was certain meals - you know, meat pies and things which I always liked better than some of the other meals and being the younger boy - one of the younger boys the older boys g
ot the - the best foods and we were always disappointed because if we had a certain meal that we really liked we were most anxious to get that and we didn't get it sometimes. The older boys were served first and there wasn't enough the younger boys had to
 
make to with what was left. Well the meal was all right but it wasn't perhaps tasty. You know what children are for meat pies and things. And the - the thing I remember mostly about that strangely enough is that I never liked cabbage when I was a boy and 
today I like it quite a lot. Used to have - used to have it at - Agecroft and; to me when I was nine or ten, it was and anathema - cabbage. I liked beans like all children like pulses and things like that but cabbage - not at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What was the average day in boarding school - what did you do?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh yes. We used to get up about eight o'clock and we had a long wash room which; was also used as a darkroom because we did photography there and about ten or more boys could wash at a time. There were about
 - fifty to sixty boys in this school and it varied from about sixteen years of age down to about eight or nine. And we used to wash in sort of groups of ten, there were so many wash bowls, and we used to wash ourselves and then we had morning prayers aft
er we washed ourselves then we used to have short exercises, sort of athletic exercises, then we used to have breakfast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What did breakfast }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 consist}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well breakfast would be - oh I remember have - we had fried eggs quite a lot. You see they did
n't have bacon or anything like that but they had fried eggs. We had porridge, fried eggs - they didn't go in for cereals in those days you know - these - you know, manufactured cereals were quite unknown with the exception of - there was one which is a s
eparate story - shredded wheat was popular in those days because an uncle of mine who became - went vegetarian went mad on that. But I never remember having any cereals at school at all. It was either }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 porridge}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  - we used to have kippers. Kippers we would hav
e. And - we even had finnan haddock. Kippers, finnan haddock, fried eggs, porridge and toast and marmalade or bread and butter and marmalade.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What did you have for lunch?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh meat and two veg quite regularly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 And tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 And - no, we never had tea - don't have tea after -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I mean teatime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh for tea. Used to have - afternoon tea we used to have tea and cake. Because, as I say, after breakfast used to go to school. We had the classes you see. And we'd have classes from nine 'til twelve - normal classes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What did you think of the teachers - were they good?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
They were very - we were with them all the time you know. And we got quite used to them. One of the teachers was rather nice - all male teachers, no female teachers at 
all because they were all boys and - the teachers were a bit, you know - the sort of people who'd only get jobs at these cheap - well, it wasn't a cheap boarding school but it wasn't a very high grade boarding school. So you didn't get the very best maste
rs although the headmaster was a - a minister and a master of Arts. But his son also taught, oh I'm sorry, his daughter taught as well. And the - class of teaching wasn't bad at all. Wasn't bad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Were they very strict though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 They weren't terribly
 strict but they were like - I don't remember it being very different from any other class and the - the boys behaved themselves just the same way, they were quite well behaved because they came from decent families, there were no - ragamuffins you know t
here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How often were you allowed to go home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Every summertime we went home. We never went home except during the summertime because we had I think six or seven weeks holiday. And if you remember I may have told you that on one occasion - I was on
ly there two years - so we came home once for six weeks, the second year me mother came and stayed for seven weeks in Margate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you want to go away to boarding school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Were you homesick when you got there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 No, not at all. N
o. Well you see there were seven of us at home and with seven you were a bit glad to get out of the way. And three of us went you see, mother couldn't have coped with seven. So she only had to cope with four - after the three of us and I'm not quite sure 
what happened to the other four when me mother came and stayed with us for seven weeks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You had a maid didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 We had a maid yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What did the maid do at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 She looked after the children, she washed the children and - did I tell
 you the story about - the one that I tell a lot of people. Me mother used to tell this story. We had a maid called Kate and for some reason or other Kate had to go away. And we had another maid and after a couple of days I went crying to me mother why co
u
ldn't we have Kate back? So she said, why? So - my answer was - she always said - I think it's quite humourous in its way I said that when Kate washed us we were clean for three days. And this new maid cleaned us every day you see which I didn't like, so 
it was apparent that Kate missed so on one or two occasions so we were clean for three days. Me mother told me this story and I retale that for over the last fifty years I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 And the maids lived in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 The maids lived in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How did you address them and how they address you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh, by their name. They used to call Mrs - Mrs Cahm it would be you see. These maids, a lot of them were youngsters from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Ireland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. But we had - this Kate was an older woman. And she was like a nanny in a way you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 She mostly dealt with you children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
She dealt with the children - she must have done work in the house. But - we weren't, you know, proper maids really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did they live in with you - eat with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 They lived in - oh yes, they lived in and they ate with us, yes. Oh yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 At the same table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Yes, at the same table, there was no distinction at all. I think I also told you there were families where the father and mother ate butter and the children ate margarine, but that never happen
ed in our house. Buy there were - no, it's not that we were too wealthy, they never made that distinction. They didn't want to deprive the children you see. I can remember I used to go to the Maypole in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Leicester Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} there and buy best butter. Remember th
ey used to have these two paddles and they used to paddle it up and do this - with water and of course a great day used to go for this. I think we used to get it for less than a shilling a pound - about a shilling a pound. Real - what they call - what the
y call best butter. We often - when we hear on the television now when people talk about best butter it reminds us of those days when the - there must have been }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 
up teen}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  kinds of butter, and margarine was about fourpence or fivepence a pound, it was like axl
e grease in those days but it must have been whale stuff or animal fat. But - we always had butter. As long as I can remember it was butter although when we were on hard times I think we had margarine - after me father died if me mother had to go to work 
remember I said she went working in the cap works, things were a bit hard that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
In those days before 1918 people used to divide society into different classes or groups - could you tell me which the different ones were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well - I can tell you
 - I don't know much about the non-Jewish ones but about the Jewish ones there was a - a class amongst the Jewish community of the better off ones, people like the Laski's and the finburgs and the Candles and Jacobs and one or two others who were - were q
u
ite wealthy in their way. There were many factories of - waterproof manufacturers, like Philip Cohen of Cohen and Wilkes, the big - were big men and they were - sort of aristocrats. And the rest of the community - were mainly small - either market people 
or machine hands or pressers tailors people or cabinet makers or decorators.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Would there be a big class distinction in the Jewish community?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh yes. There - there were hardly any middle - middle classes. It was either these aristocrats who were 
- amongst the wealthy people and the ordinary people, there wasn't much - there were a few who were perhaps a little better off. You see, let me - let me give you this - impression. You take some of the meaner streets, they're all gone now, the one they c
alled {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Magnolia Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 are very much like it, was where the people who lived there would be operative. They would be people who were pressers in a - a tailoring factory or tailors or machine hands or they'd work at Ellisons or Leichsteins cabinet works or th
ey would be - well all kinds - all kinds, they didn't go in for mechanical trade, they weren't in the engineering at all. They would be - those sort of trades. Decorators and such like, glaziers. And they were just ordinary working class people who worked
 for a master. Then there would be a few masters who would be slightly better off who would live in places like {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Bignor Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Did you ever know 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Bignor Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 Well}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 , those were much bigger houses, big old Victorian houses where they were much better off, bu
t they weren't the aristocrats. The aristocrats were those who lived in Smedley Lane, the front of Bury - Bury New Road where the Nahums lived, you know where this Bishop's Palace is - of - opposite there's a nunnery isn't there. Well Park Hall belonged t
o the Nahums and further along was the Frankemburgs. Well they were the big people, Philip Frankemburg and Alderman Frankemburg, Alderman Goldsmidt and the Quass Cohen and all those people were all big manufacturers you know, they were very wealthy.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What class would you say you belonged to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh they were poorer classes. The work - the working class. No, before me father died we really belonged to the professional classes. The lower professional classes. Perhaps lower middle class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 And then afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
And then we thought we were quite poor you see and I think we've come back to lower middle classes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a certain class of people and; why do you think it was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes. We always though
t that our family were a respectable family were held in high esteem because my grandfather was a - a lay minister. He was a - a bit of a poet, he was a bookbinder, he used to do this pas }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 pat out}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  of texts and things and he used to go visiting - outside com
munities and acting as a minister at - on certain occasions and we were quite a respectable family, yes. We weren't well known.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Who would the employers mix with in the Jewish community?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh they would mix with themselves, they -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What about the Rabbi's and the ministers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh well the Rabbi's and ministers were a special class, you see, amongst the Jewish people there was an impression that there was an }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 aristocracy}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  of brains. People who were clever were looked up to - and there were many J
ewish doctors who were really sons of poor families who, because they were able to train for doctors sort of lifted themselves out of the lower classes and very often }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7426541 Married}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  into better class families.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 So in the district where you lived who would be 
considered the most important people?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh the most important people at one time was Nathan Laski. In fact he was a Justice of the Peace and quite a quite a big men in a way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 This was because he was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 wealthy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 He was a shipper and all the rest of it, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 This is why he was considered important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Do you remember anyone being called Sir or Madam - do you remember ever having to call anyone sir or madam or having to touch your cap to anyone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh well, I - I 
belonged to the Jewish Lads Brigade and all these aristocrats that I was telling you about, these top Jewish people like the Finburts and the Nahums and that, they were officers and we called them sir. Now I don't know whether your son would know the firm
 
because has not very far away from the big firm of Barlow and Chidlows on Broad Street and round there, well the manager or the chairman of Barlow and Chidlows was Edward C.Q. Henriques who was the - the commandant of the Jewish Lads Brigade, he was a ver
y big man in the reform - not the reform club - the engineers club - he was the President at one time. He was an engineer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 This was before 1918 was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh yes, he was - he was a Major in the Royal Engineers in 1914, he was a managing director of 
Barlow and Childlows and he was a mechanic engineer and - we called him sir, in fact during the - the 1939 war he was the chief air raid warden in our district. He was the big man, the boss.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 As a boy looking at the community as a whole.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 We'd call them sir. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Did you notice any difference between the people who went to church and the people who went to chapel - as a Jewish person did you observe any difference between them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes. We always thought that the chapel people were strict
er and more - less inclined to worldly things. Oh definitely. Yes. You see, as I say I sent to St Jouns school and St Johns was connected with St Johns church and St Johns church, for instance the coming holiday like Whit Week, they used to turn out with 
the Church of England crowd and march and - and the Methodist did very little of that, they didn't have fancy banners, they were very very austere you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You think this was the difference between the two?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh yes, there were - there were - I lived in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Therlmere Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 and at the tope there was a Methodist chapel - either a Baptist or a Methodist chapel which was very severe and - oh, the solemn people. The church people are much jollier I thought.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You didn't think there was any social difference between them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 They didn't mix a lot you know. They didn't mix a lot. No, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Let's go on to your Strangeways days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Did you ever feel there that one group felt itself superior to the rest? Were some families thought of as rough and some as respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh definitely. There were - you see, the - the rough ones were those who were noisy and coarse and swore. They never swore in our house at all. No, no. They might have acquired a bit of swearing when I was in the wo
rks you know, the big works at Trafford Park but I never swore in our house, nobody ever swore in our house. Me moth - me mother never swore but there were women who used to swear and they looked down on them very much, they used to call them coarse. And 
a
s you know most Jewish people, particularly Jewish women were non-drinkers, they never drank - never got drunk. You - you wouldn't know Garnet Street in Hightown would you. Well there was one pub up there on Saturday night when they turned them out of the
 pub, there were women there, they were roaring.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 But they weren't Jewish women?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No, never saw - in fact, you saw very few Jewish men in pubs at all. Very. They're very abstemious - very abstemious indeed. There's probably more drinking goes on a
mongst the Jewish community - in my day, in fact a lot of the men wouldn't be seen inside a pub, it wasn't respectable to go into a pub. For Jewish people. In fact they used to have a certain prejudice but the non-Jewish people who frequented pubs and the
 Jewish people didn't. Now there was never any evidence of drunkenness at all amongst the Jewish people - they weren't drinkers. They're still not drinkers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Tell me about the Strangeways area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 This is quite a large Jewish area wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 It was very Jewish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Can you tell me how you observed the different classes there as a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well there were shopkeepers who had a - a little bit more money than anybody else but all the side streets like Julius Street and Dewhurst Stre
et and Irwell Street all those side streets off Bury Road between Broughton Lane and Great - Great Ducie Street, and Southhall Street and that there were all - the people were very poor people indeed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What would this mean in actual terms of living?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well - those who - perhaps had periods during the slack season of the tailoring when they had no work at all. And there was no dolw or anything like that. And what happened to those that just hadn't got used to go to the soup kitchen, there was what th
ey called the Jewish Soup Kitchen and that was at the - the working mens club at the top of Southhall Street just past the prison, there was a big building there and near there was what they called the Jewish Soup Kitchen. And you could go there and get s
oup and - a bit of a meal if you were in need.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How many times a day could you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh only the once a day. Only once a day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you observe a lot of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 poverty}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  in Strangeways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 They had - there was this - let me tell you - perhaps - go on f
rom that. And there was also what they called the Jewish Board of Guardians. And on Cheetham Hill Road at the corner of - is it Broughton Street - there's a big building, I think it's called Frankemburg House and that was called the Jewish Board of Guardi
a
ns. And if you - wanted you could go there and you could get a - a sub - some money. Perhaps two shillings or half a crown or perhaps up to five shillings a week. It was a charity and the Jewish people used to go there to the Board of Guardians and of cou
rse it was a great disgrace - or they felt it was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 disgrace}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 if you had to go and - either go to the soup kitchen or the - Board of Guardians and these aristocrats that I'm telling you about, they used to have functions throughout the year for the soup kitc
hen and for the Board of Guardians. And for the Jewish hospital too you know. They were the highlights of the season and all the best people went to these balls. These were for these Jewish charities. And - oh there were lots of people who used - they use
d
 to get clothing to at the Board of Guardians. In fact, in later years I have sent old beds that they've been either collected or I've taken mattresses and other things to the same place for distribution amongst the old people - stuff we were getting rid 
of.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
In the Jewish community did you feel it was possible to move from one class to another?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh it - it - it happened. It happened because the origins of some of the wealthiest people today were very - I can tell you something about my own relati
ons. Now - there's a - a firm which is world wide known, goes under the name of Vantona. You've heard of Vantona? You know Vantona do you? Well the chairman of Vantona is my first cousin. Basil Glass. Do you know where Basil Glass lived? At the the side o
f South }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 Manchester}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 synagogue - South Broughton synagogue - is - was Sabrina Street and there was - there were about three or four houses and my aunt and uncle lived there and they were as poor as church mice. As poor as church }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 mice}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well how do you think they managed to move up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well I'll tell you how they managed - well my aunt was a very very clever woman. She was originally a shirt maker. And she worked as a shirt maker for years and my uncle was a - a tailor but he never did very much at all a
nd she then started making gowns. She went from shirt making to gowns. And eventually - she managed to get a bit of a workshop in town, in Turner Street, and there is still a place, the - J - J Glass and Co. in Turner Street was the originally my aunt's p
lace. It now belongs to somebody called Dudley Glass but the Vantoana people are not connected with it. And they went on from there to open a shop in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Market Street
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and they went from dire poverty to vast riches - I think my cousin must be a millionaire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 And you think they did it through hard work obviously?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
They - my aunt was a very very smart woman and she was a very - how shall it put it - hard woman too. Very - very business like and - oh - because she's been dead a long time - and she was stone }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 deaf}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
. And - I had to shout in her ear and she was quite unscrupulous as well. Quite unscrupulous. My other cousin - Julius Glass who was the joint managing director, he's gone too and I don't think they'll, you know - have me up for libel or anything lik
e that but she was a very hard woman. Very hard. The only thing we ever got cut of her - when my brother was very ill and we had to send him away to a private nursing home I and me mother went to this aunt and after a lot of persuasion she paid the fee fo
r - I think a three month session in this place. We got things out of her but you had to work very hard. She never - do you know that she never gave me a wedding present. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Were there other methods of getting to the top and moving - do you think peop
le could move from one class to another in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh yes, they - they moved - as I say some of the wealthiest people - that's one that I've mentioned, who went from rags to riches. The - the ones Cohen and Wilkes you know. Philip Quess Cohen his
 father was a - they call him Fatzel Cohen, that was his Jebrew name - was quite a poor man in his day and Philip Quass Cohen, well his name's Philip Cohen, he }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7426541 Married}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  Dorothy Quasnik, they changed their name to Quess Cohen, and her father must have been a wealthy man and he }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7426541 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 into money and became the owner of a very big factory. Let's see some of the other factories. Oh all the big waterproofers - waterproof people. Were - a lot of them are very humble origins. But some of them, the people I'm telli
ng you about - the Nahums and the Mandleburgs and those I think I had been in England for many years, they weren't immigrants at all and they were already established.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
In the Jewish community before 1918 do you remember a distinction between craftsmen and labourers at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
We never had any labourers. There were never any Jewish labourers. No. They never went in for manual labouring. There were - they were all in these trades that I've mentioned but - craft trades, but they were never labourers at
 all. Very very - I don't think one in a thousand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Between semi-skilled and skilled there was a big difference?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No, a lot of them were really - they weren't semi'skilled, they were skilled. All either pressers or machine hands or cutters or deco
rators or cabinet makers, Ellisons and Eeichsteins and some of the other big cabinet places were full of Jewish cabinet makers. In fact the trade on Ancotts is still in the hands of the Jewish people.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Do you ever remember any labourers round Strangew
ays and do you remember a distinction between craftsmen and labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well I think they - I think they looked down on - especially on the Irish labourers who used to get drunk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Do you remember the Irish labourers when you were at Strangeways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I do. I do, yes. I do that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Do you think it was possible to move from one class to another before 1918?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Do you mean amongst the Jewish people? Oh they did - they did it regularly because what - what happened, you know, was that they started
 in Morton Street at the back of Victoria station and round about there you know where Cockchoots is. They moved from there to say Hightown or Cheetham and from }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 
T}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 heetham they went to Broughton and from Broughton some of them have gone to Gatley and Cheadle
 and Hale and - all steps up, yes, oh yes. Now there's - there are many families who live in Hale who have got very humble - humble - I've got - I've got a niece who was born in where was she born, I think in Dudley Street. Well 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Dudley Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} was next door to a slum if it wasn't a slum.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Were there slums in Hightown in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh yes. Garnet Street was shocking. Peter Street - Peter Street and Water Street all the streets, they're all knocked down now, Marlborough Road ran from somewhere near 
Waterloo Road to Great Cheetham Street, did you know it at all, Marlborough Road? All the little streets like Peter Street, Water Street and Charlotte Street were all - houses were - their doors were right on the pavements and there were - there were just
 
a little bit better than two up and two down. And they were peopled by poor Jewish families, you know, some of these work - ordinary workers and a lot of poor Christian families. And - they were very poor people there. Oh very poor indeed. There were one 
o
r two who were more respectable but - I still think it's true and I think people would confirm this, that they never - see the Jewish people never went into certain trades, they never went into the engineering trade, they never went into the construction 
business, either as labourers or as - there were a few builders, very few but there were a few }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 builders}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Why do you think this was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well they just didn't get into those trades. That's one of the reasons they just well now they're attractive but t
here were some other reasons. The fact that they were Jewish and they would have to have Jewish holidays and the Sabbath would interfere with it, some people didn't want to work on the Sabbath you see, that meant that they'd want to knock off sometime on 
a Friday night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 So you would be more or less compelled }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11168726\charrsid1644444 to}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  stay with a Jewish firm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Compelled to stay with - see there were many boys who weren't able to go into a big non-Jewish firms because their parents knew that they wouldn't be able to get S
aturdays off and they wouldn't get Jewish holidays off. In fact, as a boy - I remember one of these aristocrats that I'm telling you ab}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 out who was a big man}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  - man in the Jewish Lads Brigade and the Grove House Lads Club came to see the - one of the management people at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Trafford{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 for me to have the Jewish holidays off. Did you know that? Well Metro Vickers was a very cosmopolitan place and there was no difficulty about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How did you find the Jewish community as a whole before 1918 do you think t
hey chose to stay together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 They were very - they were very close - they were very close together, yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Why was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well I think it was protection more than anything else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 But you say there was no prejudice?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well, when I say 
there was no prejudice, there was no prejudice because they kept very strictly apart. And they didn't have much contact. You see, when you talk about prejudice you've got to be very careful who - in which way prejudice works. You get the sort of prejudice
 
where a Jewish person might have difficulty in getting a job in - in a non-Jewish firm who would be prejudiced against them in that, in fact it occurred to me when I went from the - the Grammar school to a chemists as an apprentice, they wouldn't have me 
b
ecause I was Jewish you see and it was a Jewish chemist too. So that was a queer sort of prejudice. But - you see - it's very hard to define prejudice. They - they say that it's a sort of irrational feeling - it's based on fear, a lot of the non-Jewish pe
ople were frightened of the Jewish but - they thought they had horns sticking out of their heads.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 This is your memory from childhood is it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh it's - I think it's very much like that today in many cases. But they - because they were kept apart an
d they didn't know much about each other they get all sorts of wrong impressions of - what they're like. And in my day you know if a - a Jewish boy went out with a non - Jewish girl there was a scandal about it. Very much so. Oh yes, they - they thought i
t was awful. There were cases, one or two I can remember very successful cases where there were mixed marriages. But it was - there were - the world was nearly coming to an end if there was a mixed - any thought of a mixed marriage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Do you remember your mother telling you about this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh - well she didn't brainwash me but she always mentioned about it and she always encouraged me not to - get involved with any non-Jewish girls. But, strangely enough, I never had the inclination to do that. Mind you
, some of the more - you know - how shall I say - gay boys, we used to go }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 straggling}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  and it was quite an achievement to pick up a non-Jewish girl you know. Yes. And - but - but they never got serious with them. They used to play about with them but never got serious.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 But they never played about with a Jewish girl you said?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh no, no, no. If they went out with a Jewish girl about twice the mother wanted to know if they had any intentions. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Tell me how your marriage came about - did you have a matchmaker?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No. The wife and I are related you know. So I knew my wife from early age. I knew her from a girl you see. And we were thrown - remember me telling you about going to me grandmothers - well she would be there. And it must have bee
n there I formed an attachment for her because they always thought I would go off with her elder sister.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 But you didn't have a matchmaker?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Not at all, no. Although my younger brother I think was - his marriage was arranged through - what they ca
ll a shaplin, which is a matchmaker. It was really introductions rather than matchmaking. You see, my mother always thought that I might marry a wealthy girl, as I told you there was supposed to be an aristocracy of brains and if you were a little bit abo
v
e the average you weren't going to be a machiner or a cutter, you were going to be something better, after all I went to the Grammar school you knew and the Grammar school was held in high esteem even in those days and they thought perhaps I was going to 
b
e something more and she had her eyes on the daughter of a - a man called - I think he's dead now - he was a - a meat wholesaler, he was a butcher. And he used to have a very big wholesale place and he had a daughter of marriageable age - I never met this
 girl although }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11168726\charrsid1644444 strangely}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 enough - although strangely enough a cou - a distant cousin of me }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7426541 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 a - a granddaughter and this - this girl, she must have }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7426541 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 somebody else, and my mother had worked it but it never came off. I was going to be introduced
 to this girl. And with the - you know - well it didn't get that far - I went out with a girl. We used to have, as I told you I used to belong to the Jewish Lads Brigade And Grove House Lads Club and that was on Bury New Road where Nunns is, you know the 
g
reat big place, well that was where our club was and right opposite was the Jewish girls club and the Jewish girls club was run by these aristocratic ladies - Mrs Henriques was the big lady there and some of the other - Mrs Finburg and all the big ladies 
were sort of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 manageress\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 and of course they used that so that the boys and girls could come together. And there was a girl there - her name was Eskinasi but she had hair like the actress Maisie Mowber and I took this girl Eskinasi cut for a long time. In f
act it was getting serious. I took her to Metro Vick, I took her to Stretford to a dance there, I took her to a number of dances and I took her to of course the Brigade, we used to have her and somewhere I've got a photograph of this girl, she's dead now 
by the way - I met her in later life and she was still lovely girl - a lovely woman. I met her - that must have been 1917 - 1918 round about that time. I met her again about thirty years lager when she was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7426541 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  and had two group up children and - she wen
t to live in Blackpool and strangely enough she knew my sister-in-law, but she died.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 When you left school and went to work you still lived at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 At home, yes, until I was 19 - until about 1923 and then left.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did starting full time work 
change your relationship with your parents or your brothers at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
It was just me mother. Yes. You see, my mother knew that had I - I - I had been to the Grammar school she didn't want me to go into one of these waterproof workshops or tailoring wor
kshops because she thought that wasn't the place for me, after all I'd had a better education than some of the other boys. My brother had to come out of school when he was fourteen and he started working in a waterproof factory when he didn't - when he di
d
n't go on markets and that and she didn't - she was prepared to sacrifice - I didn't want to - I wanted to go to work to get some money you see. So she was prepared to sacrifice what while I went to become an apprentice. And - I went to Metro Vick for fiv
e shillings a week. No, six shillings a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did it change your attitude to your mother at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh no, no, no - no. Although, although I think I told you, the first day I came back from Metro Vick I said, I'm not going back again. But she persuaded me to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you still go to the synagogue after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Yes. Yes. Went - for quite a time. And then I went at least twice a year. I left the choir when I was about - thirteen or fourteen. But I went every Saturday and to choir pra
ctice and to every holiday 'cos I were on this choir you know, for the money. Like they say on the advert - I'm only there for the money. And I was in the - the - the trebles, I was a treble. Never a very good singer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Were you interested in politics as you started to grow up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Not until - oh I was about thirty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 This would be after 1918 wouldn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Yes, oh yes. I wasn't interested in politics at all. Not at all. I was interested in the Brigade you see, in the Boys Club. I joined the boy
s club in 1914. The year the war broke out and I joined it mainly because they had draughts and chess and ping-pong at this club. But one of the conditions of joining the club was that you had to join the Jewish Lads Brigade which was a Boys Brigade and -
 oh I was quite an important man in the brigade, I became the bandmaster.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You continued with this after you started work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh until I - until I was about twenty-two.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How did your habits change - did you go out in the evening more when you wer
e working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
We went three or four times a week to the club and we had drill - we had drill twice a week in the drill hall you see. We went to camp once a year. And - when I wasn't going there - I don't know if I ever told you that - this love that my 
father and mother had for the music hall came to me because from about 1916 'til about 1920 I and two other boys went regularly to the Manchester Hippodrome every week and we had two - three seats in the front row of the gods throughout the season and you
 
could - there was an arrangement whereby if you went and said we went a regular seat there the only sixpence in those days you had to confirm or get your tickets before Friday night. And I saw all the leading music hall turns of the - of the day from abou
t 1917 - '16-'17 up to about 1920.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Didn't you start going out with girls when you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
No, the only time - I didn't go out with girls really. We met the girls at the girls club when I - as I say I joined this when I was fourteen and lect
 when I was over twenty so in the meantime we used to see the girls there but the two boys that I went out with we never chased after girls. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Did your mother expect to meet your friends and were you expected to bring them home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Well not so mu
ch as I went to the friends home - I nearly lived in one chap's home and I used to go there regularly, he had sisters and they used to eye me up and the sisters you know but - never seriously, I think I was too young really -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you have to be home by a certain time when you were working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Not - not really, me mother - I wasn't a bad boy, I never had any bad habits you know so I never stayed out very late so me mother - mother had never any trouble with me at all in that respect.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 In the dist
rict where you lived if anyone did anything wrong that the community disapproved of how did they show their disapproval - was there anything particularly special to the Jewish community?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes, if a Jewish boy got a - got a girl into a trouble - they w
ere more or less ostracized you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Just sent them to Coventry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh they had - wouldn't have anything to do with them, no. They were very bad that way. And - they also didn't like - you see a few Jewish people they went bankrupt or fraud and went to prison and they avoided them like the plague. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 This was considered wrong was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes, oh yes. They didn't take kindly to that at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What happened once the Jewish boy and girl go }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7426541 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 , surely they would be accepted back into the Jewish community again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
They'd go and live in another district. Any one like that - they weren't accepted at all. You see to - today it's different. I belong to a community, the reform synagogue who will accept non-Jews into the community buy the 
orthodox ones don't. They're very strict.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 So if they }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7426541 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  a non-Jewish girl this would be another thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
They would separate them quite from the community - they wouldn't have anything to do with them, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 So if they went bankrupt or got a girl into trouble or -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
You see, the incidents of crime amongst the Jewish people is very low indeed, you can search the archive and you'll find that - violent crimes are very rare, there was a case where somebody I think committed a murder with th
e - a pair of shears many years ago in Strangeways.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Why do you think this was?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
It wasn't their nature to be violent. They put it down to a number of reasons. One was that they were more literate because of the connection with the Jewish religio
n and the - how close the religion was to them - the other was that - by nature they weren't violent people, remember they were immigrants and they were careful not to - you know - to cause trouble. They had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 pogrom}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  in the places where they came from. They didn't want it -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Do you remember a policeman round where you lived when you were a child and how you felt about him and how he treated the people? Were you ever threatened by your mother about a policeman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh yes. Oh yes, you were threatened by 
your mother - I'll call a policeman, yes. The bobby. They did that the same way they did to any other child you know. The people they used to frighten them with - the bogey man, was always the bogey man. They used to frighten them with the dustbin men as 
well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Why the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 dustbin man}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Because he was big and ugly and - dirty you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Were you afraid of the police?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How do you think he treated the people - the Jewish people in Strangeways?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 He got very friendly with them at tim
es. He did that. Because they used to make a fuss of him - non-Jewish policemen - because you can imagine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well it was the habit amongst a lot of Jewish people to treat non-Jews better than Jews you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 I don't know whethe
r it was they wanted to be considered or felt that they were being friendly to them or - to be held high in their estimation but there was a - a kind of a - I don't know how to explain it, but they had a much - you know - a - better attitude towards non-J
ews than their - some did and some didn't of course. Some were very - you know - you know - how shall I put it - sarcastic and that about them and treated them a bit }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 contemptuously}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 . But a lot of others were very different, they used to - they used to fall o
ver them -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How did the police treat people in Strangeways and in Hightown?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Oh there was very little trouble - very little trouble - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You think he treated them fairly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 They treated them fairly, oh yes. But I - I don't recall any vio
lent incidents in my - now my recollection would be from about say seven - age seven until about - twenty or even more, twenty-four and I cannot remember any really serious things, not like any they had in London, they had all sorts of things in the East 
E
nd of London you know but in Strangeways, occasionally you'd get a non-Jewish person would fall out with a Jewish person and call them all sorts of names and shout in the streets and all the Jewish people would go into their houses and get out of the way,
 
they wouldn't start any arguments and unless some of the boys you know became boxers and they'd stand up for themselves. But a lot of the Jewish boys, they weren't - very good at sticking up for themselves so they kept out of the way. But of course some o
f
 them became very good athletes and some of them were very good boxers. And - I had - one of these boys that I used to - three of us used to go together and one of these had an uncle who was a professional boxer and he was very friendly with a - well it w
a
s a champion - a fellow called Joe Bowker who I think was a middleweight champion of Britain and had a - a boxing school - gym - somewhere in - oh Rochdale Road and occasionally I used to go with this boy to watch them and he was treated the same as any o
ther - he was very friendly with them and I don't think there was any real }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 antagonism}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  between them. You see, I - I may - perhaps my experience didn't run to that but I don't recall a lot of bitterness a - I told you about these kids tying balls of paper and
 mobbing each other at election time. But we - I don't remember having fights with a non-Jewish children. And all where I lived there were streets and streets where there were no Jes at all. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Emerson Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} which was the next street to ours wa}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11168726\charrsid1644444 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  entirely non-Jewish, and there were children there who used to see at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11168726\charrsid1644444 school}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 . }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11168726\charrsid1644444 N}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 ow in the playground at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}St Johns{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 we used to play really and Jewish children and Christian children used to play together and there was never any trouble. I can't remember any trouble at all.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Do you think your mother and father had the same attitude to people in all groups and classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well my mother and father were much closer to non-Jews than most of the Jews because my father had a lot of contact with non-Jewish people you see.
 In fact he was in a kind of partnership with two non-Jews and my mother used to meet them socially. And - so that she - she knew a lot of non-Jewish people and she got on very well with non-Jewish people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you think they had the same attitude to p
eople in different classes or groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well I'll tell you what happened, there was a certain kind of feeling that if there were Jewish people who couldn't speak English properly - broken English - and weren't very Anglicized in their ways they were in
clined to scoff and - be sarcastic and - despise those - that type of Jew.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Yet you would have thought their sympathy would have been towards them having come from another country?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Not at all. No. No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 They used to laugh at the
m and mock after them as well. The boys - of course, I don't know whether you know the term sheeny. Well - that was the - Gentile word for a New - you're a sheeny. Go on, you dirty sheeny. Of course all Jews were dirty you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 They were always referred to as dirty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
always referred to as dirty Jew, yes. You see the impression they got from Shylock and from Fagin and all the rest of it is very hard to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Was your home rented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Yes. All the homes were all rented - yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you ever meet any of your landlords and what did you feel about them?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Never met the landlord. No. Only contact would be a rent book or somebody came collecting, that's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Tell me about life after your father died and your mother had such a strug
gle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 That was - that was - that was bad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 It would be a sudden change for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
You see, we lived in Sedgley Park at the time in - Richmond Avenue and it was a very nice house, it's not - it's there - typing bureau at the m
oment. It was a corner house, it was a very nice house indeed and - we lived - oh I suppose we must have been sort of comfortable life, my father, according to what my mother told me, used to draw three pound a week. Three pound a week - you didn't do too
 
badly in 1911 because there were clerks who were - bringing families up up to 1914 on twenty-five shillings a week and draughtsmen were supposed to be the elite of the engineering industry and up to about 1914 they used to get round about three pound a we
ek so it was quite a good wage, that's what he drew. So we didn't live so badly. Not only that, from his commissions he was able to send us to this boarding school you see. Even in the worst possible moments I never remember going hungry.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 But you would have a big drop in your standard when your father died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well I wouldn't - what - what I would notice most would be - clothing and things of that kind and amusement. We had to leave {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Richmond Avenue{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 as you can imagine. The house was - we couldn't kee
p it on. In order to try and sort of get some money my mother's brothers organized a ball in aid of my mother. I don't think they made very much money out of it. And - they realized that she had no means - she - couldn't really go out to work so they - th
ey - got up sufficient money for her to buy a shop. And we went to live in a shop at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}108 Vury New Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Which wasn't very successful and it was only because my grandmother and grandfather and my uncle and aunt came to live with us and the - me uncle and aunt were working that we managed to keep the shop going you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What kind of shop was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Grocery shop. A small grocery shop. Well it didn't last }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 v}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
ery long. And then from there we went to another grocery shop further down, still with the family l
iving with us. And the top floor of this house was turned into a workshop to - in order to - get some extra rent. Well this was - there were three floors in this - building, and we lived - the shop was on the bottom floor, we - all the bedrooms on the nex
t
 floor and the top floor was this - workshop - it was a tailors workshop. But that didn't last very long because I think we ate most of the protits. Big family - there was quite a crowd to be kept you see. Then - steps were - were taken to relieve me moth
er and two of my brothers were sent off to this - orphan school in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. So there were only five of us left. And the five of us then went into 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Howarth Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, this street at the back of - you know, the Gardeners Arms - the Cricketers Arms and we lived in 
a - well it was rally a hovel there. It was bug ridden, we had lodgers there and me mother went to a cap works to work. And - I went from there to the Grammar school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
How did you feel at the time about her having to struggle so hard to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
I - no, being young I - it didn't - it didn't hurt me, I didn't - I wasn't sensitive very much to it. As long as I got enough to eat I didn't seem to worry. I used to do little things - if you remember my uncle had a workshop in town and I used to d
o on Friday afternoon after school, work in the workshop, take the - trousers, after they'd been cut, to the trouser maker - and used to have a - I don't know whether you've ever seen these - large bundle ever your shoulder with a black alpaca cape over i
t
, well I used to take those to the - workshops, the outworkers. I used to pull all the bastings out of the tyr-ons. Do you know how they make try-one with gents - and lots of basting on the front of the canvass. Well it was my job to pull the bastings out
 when the things had been - sort of machined and the - they take the bastings out. And then it was my job to take all the parcels to the tramway office in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Moseley Street
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - down a basement there was the corporation tram place. And - I used to take parcels th
ere and - I also used to take parcels to different - customers around the town. I got to know the town pretty well. In addition to that I used to take - grocery orders out for a shop nearby and we had a little - well it was really a sugar box on wheels - 
did you ever see the little trucks that boys used to make? Used to get a - pram wheels and fasten the sugar box on them and two wooden handles and I used to take orders out for one of the shops Finegoes or -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You didn't feel resentful at your big drop in circumstances?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh no. No, no, no. It was - it was a - it was a joke - it was a bit of a joke. No, as I say, as long as I wasn't hungry - and even, as I say, when - Payton - J.L. Payton who was the high master of the Grammar school must have known o
r somebody noticed that I was shabby and I got called to the office and he arranged through some fund for me to get a suit. And I - my father-in-law - uncle, he made the suit for me and the bill was presented to Mr Payton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 How did your mother feel about this drop?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Well she - I think she was very upset about it but she - there was nothing much she could do you see and she just - I suppose, had to stand it. It must have affected her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 She'd come to a vastly different district hadn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh yes. She'd had maids of course and she - been - spent six weeks in a country - in a seaside place as the mother of three children at a boarding school and she'd never been on the Continent like that but she'd been on holidays and - been mistress of a h
ouse so it was - was quite something - for her. And - so I think the effect on her that she didn't stay in the house very much. She had a friend and they used to go out to town to go to the caf\'e9
 and have a - you know, something, then she went to these tont
ine clubs. And - one or two other things. Did I ever tell you the story of her - it's in the days just when - I think - pound notes were coming. They were in gold - it was after the gold area - era and me mother and this friend of hers -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 She found a purse - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 It wasn't a purse, it was a satchel full of notes and this }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 lady\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
 name was Rosie and she - me mother always told us, she said, look Rosie, money, money, money. Something you'd never }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7762708\charrsid1644444 deemed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444  of. And there must have been - I don't know how m
any hundreds of pounds there and then a woman came up and swore blind that - she said, you saw me drop it. And they handed it over. Never got a penny of it. She told this story many times. She said there must have been hundreds of pounds in it. And that w
as the only money she ever had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
What was the general spirit on the market amongst the Jewish people on the whole - was there a lot of deep friendship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Did you ever hear of the term called run-out workers? You don't know what a run-out worker is? 
It's a man who had a stall and it's on two flat trys that are; hinged and he's the biggest rogue unhung and he'll twist you right left and centre if he can. He's the sort of man who - shows you an article and offers it you at a ridiculous price but you ha
v
e to give him this money, whatever it is, and - he finally finishes up by giving you the article providing you pay something, you know, buy it and gives you your own money back as though he's giving you something and they used to sell spurious - jewellery
 
and all kinds of things. And the Jewish fellows were very good at this game and they used to have these things and as soon as they thought the police was coming - the box went together and it was like a case and they'd just walk off as though nothing had 
happened.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 This was on the market?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
This was on the market, yes. And then - they weren't stall holders either they were doing it illicitly all the time you know. It's probably done today - similar to these chaps selling nylons, used to sell nylons on {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}
}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Margate Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and things of that kind. But it was done with watches and - jewellery and all kinds things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 And they offered you a watch and took your money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
They offered you a watch at a ridiculous price and - in order to show you - they say,
 I've chosen you, you've got an honest face, you're one of those who's going to be picked for this special bargain. Ten bob - or whatever it was. Hand your ten bobs up, you know, as sign of good faith and then they'd tack something else on and ask a sort 
o
f an overall price and by the time you'd finished you were paying about twice as much as you ought to and they'd give you all these things and he says, here's ten bob to help you to pay for it which was your own ten shillings you see. And they did it in s
u
ch a way that you didn't know you were being twisted. They were called run-out workers and - what they call Dutch auctions where they start off sometimes at a high price and they gradually come down - I won't say a pound, say fifteen shillings, no not fif
teen shillings - they were called Dutch auctions.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 You remember this happening as a boy too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh I watched them do it. In fact I helped them - I helped them to do it because they would send me out - to - say, oh there's a gentleman over there, take
 his money. And I would go and collect his money and bring it up to the auctioneer. One of my brothers did this. He did it in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Sheffield{\*\xmlclose}
 and Bakewell and round there until he - his voice broke. That way my - that was me elder brother.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 What was it like as a boy growing up in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}England{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} before 1918 - did you feel Jewish or did you feel English?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
Oh we knew we were Jewish because we - lived mainly among Jewish people and had - not a lot of contact with non-Jews.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 Did you feel more Jewish than English though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
I don't think so. You see - I joined the boys brigade when I was thirteen - not quite fourteen - and we were the only Jewish team in both the cricket league and the football league so every team we played at football were non-Jewish - in th
e boys clubs league - lads club league - and in cricket and I don't remember anything very special. Now when we were at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Margate{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 we were Jewish college and we used to play football and cricket with the other boys in the colleges and I can't remember any unpleasantness at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 We all feel that there was so much persecution.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10563112 HC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
I don't think there was - no, no. Not - not persecution as you would call it. What happened - what happened was, see what really happened was this. I was at - playing the bugle 
in the Jewish Lads Brigade they wanted to form something better so they bought some instruments - these wealthy people that I told you about - provided them with cornets so we had not only bugles but cornets and there used to be a special marching songs y
ou could use both cornets and bugles. And then - I was introduced by - I just can't remember who - who wanted to do something better than just playing a cornet. There was a Higher Broughton bass band which played in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address
}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Great Cheetham Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} just the back of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Rigby Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 there. And I went to this brass band and asked could I join. And my younger brother came with me. And - they also played, not only there but also played at a P.S.A. in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}
Hilton Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. there was a Sun - one of these Pleasant Sunday Afternoon places in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Hilton Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Where - and the band used to play there tool - Eventually they allowed me to join. But they found out the they had too many cornets - what they called third cornets - the dregs of the band you know, the least important ones and one of t
he boys in the band who played in this band also played in Eny's Street, a man called Clifford Dyper, he was a bass trombone player, and - he was very friendly with me, I don't know how I come to be friendly with him, perhaps you make friends with somebod
y
. He was about my own age. He said, you come along with me, I belong to Eny's Street band. So I went to Eny's Street and they said, well, you can take the trombone, you only have go run for a trombone. And they gave me the instrument and I started practic
i
ng and they were most kind to me, I can't remember any - I went to tea to one or two of the houses, I was friendly with the boys, I used to go out at Christmas Eve playing carols, I went with them to a house - there's a house - a big house down Whit Lane 
w
here they used to go at Christmas Eve and the people there used to make hot coffee and mince pies for them and we used to go there and we had a very good time there with these mince pies. Used to have these old acetylene lamps you know that they used to r
e
ad the music from, and then - I used to go out with the Eny's Street Sunday school, they used to have a - an anniversary and it was usually on a Sunday and I went out with the band and I was the lead - the leading man - the trom - the first trombone playe
r
 is the top right hand man and on very special occasions when the band was going down - Lower Broughton Road there - Broughton Road and wanted to turn into Gerald Road and go back to Eny's Street I turned into the other side of Gerald Road and - on my own
 
for a moment or so 'til I realized I'd - they'd turned the other way. I'd broke away - the band was a big; formation like that, I was the corner man and I should have gone round like that but they went round and I went round this way and there I was with 
me trombone running back again. And - as I say, I - I was friendly with the Hardman family. Never had any trouble with them at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2514909 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid728729\charrsid1644444 
